militias:'''<br />{{flagicon image|Flagge FDLR.svg}} [[Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda|FDLR]]\n* [[Mai-Mai]]\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of the Rwandan Democratic Movement.svg|size=23px}} [[Interahamwe]]\n* [[Republican Rally for Democracy in Rwanda|RDR]]\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of Rwanda (1962-2001).svg|size=23px}} [[Army for the Liberation of Rwanda|ALiR]]\n* Other [[Hutu]]-aligned forces\n'''Anti-Burundi militias:'''\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of the CNDD-FDD.svg|size=23px}} [[National Council for the Defense of Democracy\u2013Forces for the Defense of Democracy|CNDD-FDD]]\n* [[National Liberation Front (Burundi)|FROLINA]]\n|combatant2= '''Rwandan-aligned militias:'''\n* [[Rally for Congolese Democracy|RCD]]\n* [[Rally for Congolese Democracy\u2013Goma|RCD-Goma]]\n* [[Banyamulenge]]\n'''Ugandan-aligned militias:'''\n* [[Movement for the Liberation of Congo|MLC]]\n* [[Forces for Renewal]]\n* [[Union of Congolese Patriots|UPC]]\n* Other [[Tutsi]]-aligned forces\n'''Anti-Angolan forces:'''<br />[[File:Flag of UNITA.svg|22px|border]] [[UNITA]]<br />'''Foreign state actors:'''<br /> {{flagicon|Uganda}} [[Uganda]]<br />{{flagicon|Rwanda|1962|size=22px}} [[Rwanda]]<br />{{flagicon|Burundi}} [[Burundi]]\n----<small>Note: Rwanda and Uganda fought [[Six Day War (Kisangani)|a short war]] in June 2000 over Congolese territory.</small>\n|commander1='''DR Congo''':<br /> [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila]] <br /><small>(1997\u20132001)</small><br /> [[Joseph Kabila]]<br /> <small>(2001\u20132003)</small>\n----'''Namibia:'''<br /> [[Sam Nujoma]]<br />[[Dimo Hamaambo]]<br />[[Martin Shalli]]\n----'''Zimbabwe:'''<br /> [[Robert Mugabe]]<br /> [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]]<br /> [[Constantine Chiwenga]]<br /> [[Perence Shiri]]\n----'''Angola:'''<br /> [[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos]]<br /> [[Jo\u00e3o de Matos]]\n---- '''Chad:'''<br /> [[Idriss D\u00e9by]]\n|commander2='''MLC:'''<br />[[Jean-Pierre Bemba]]\n----'''RCD:'''<br /> [[Azarias Ruberwa]]\n----'''Tutsi groups:''' <br /> [[Laurent Nkunda]]\n----'''Uganda:'''<br /> [[Yoweri Museveni]]\n----'''Rwanda:'''<br /> [[Paul Kagame]]\n----'''Burundi:'''<br /> [[Pierre Buyoya]]\n|strength1='''Mai Mai:''' 20\u201330,000&nbsp;militia\n----'''Interahamwe:''' 20,000+\n|strength2='''RCD:''' 45,000\n----'''Rwanda:''' 8,000+<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.economist.com/world/africa/displayStory.cfm?story_id=1213296 |work=The Economist |title=Africa's great war |date=4 July 2002 |access-date=7 February 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205043254/http://www.economist.com/World/africa/displayStory.cfm?story_id=1213296 |archive-date=5 February 2007 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=2,000 Ugandans <small>(Kisangani only)</small><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.willum.com/dissertation/3rpa.PDF |title=Archived copy |access-date=25 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927214742/http://www.willum.com/dissertation/3rpa.PDF |archive-date=27 September 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><br />\n4,000 rebel casualties <small>(Kinshasa only)</small>\n|casualties3=2.7\u20135.4 million [[excess death]]s (1998\u20132008)<ref>{{cite journal |author=Coghlan B |title=Mortality in the Democratic Republic of Congo: a nationwide survey |journal=Lancet |volume=367 |issue=9504 |pages=44\u201351 |date=January 2006 |pmid=16399152 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(06)67923-3 |author2=Brennan RJ |author3=Ngoy P |display-authors=3 |last4=Dofara |first4=David |last5=Otto |first5=Brad |last6=Clements |first6=Mark |last7=Stewart |first7=Tony |url=http://conflict.lshtm.ac.uk/media/DRC_mort_2003_2004_Coghlan_Lancet_2006.pdf |accessdate=27 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426073502/http://conflict.lshtm.ac.uk/media/DRC_mort_2003_2004_Coghlan_Lancet_2006.pdf |archive-date=26 April 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[Staff] (20100120) [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8471147.stm \"DR Congo war deaths 'exaggerated'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100121025213/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8471147.stm |date=21 January 2010 }} BBC News</ref>\n350,000+ violent deaths (1998\u20132001)<ref>International Rescue Committee ([undated]) [http://www.theirc.org/special-reports/congo-forgotten-crisis Congo Crisis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829000947/http://www.theirc.org/special-reports/congo-forgotten-crisis |date=29 August 2010 }} International Rescue Committee</ref><ref>Les Roberts & others (2001) [http://www.rescue.org/sites/default/files/resource-file/2001%20Mortality%20Survey.pdf Mortality in eastern Democratic Republic of Congo: Results from Eleven Mortality Surveys (PDF)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427121355/http://www.rescue.org/sites/default/files/resource-file/2001%20Mortality%20Survey.pdf |date=27 April 2012 }} (Report) International Rescue Committee</ref>|}}\n{{Campaignbox Conflict in Congo}}The '''Second Congo War''', also known as '''Africa's World War''' and the '''Great War of Africa''', began in August 1998 in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] (formerly called Zaire), and officially ended in July 2003 when the Transitional Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo took power (though hostilities continue to this day). The largest war in modern [[History of Africa|African history]], it directly involved eight [[African nations]], as well as about 25 armed groups. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Makar|first=A. B.|last2=McMartin|first2=K. E.|last3=Palese|first3=M.|last4=Tephly|first4=T. R.|date=1975-06|title=Formate assay in body fluids: application in methanol poisoning|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1|journal=Biochemical Medicine|volume=13|issue=2|pages=117\u2013126|doi=10.1016/0006-2944(75)90147-7|issn=0006-2944|pmid=1}}</ref>By 2008 the war and its aftermath had killed 5.4 million people, mostly from disease and starvation, making the Second Congo War the deadliest conflict worldwide since World War II. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bose|first=K. S.|last2=Sarma|first2=R. H.|date=1975-10-27|title=Delineation of the intimate details of the backbone conformation of pyridine nucleotide coenzymes in aqueous solution|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1173\u20131179|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90482-9|issn=1090-2104|pmid=2}}</ref>Millions more were displaced from their homes or sought asylum in neighboring countries.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nDespite a formal end to the war in July 2003 and an agreement by the former belligerents to create a government of national unity, 1,000 people died daily in 2004 from easily preventable cases of malnutrition and disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bose|first=K. S.|last2=Sarma|first2=R. H.|date=1975-10-27|title=Delineation of the intimate details of the backbone conformation of pyridine nucleotide coenzymes in aqueous solution|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1173\u20131179|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90482-9|issn=1090-2104|pmid=2}}</ref>\n\n==Factions==\n\nGiven the fluid nature of the war, there have been numerous exceptions and caveats to the categorization below, and groups within a single category have violently clashed in the past over resources and territory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bose|first=K. S.|last2=Sarma|first2=R. H.|date=1975-10-27|title=Delineation of the intimate details of the backbone conformation of pyridine nucleotide coenzymes in aqueous solution|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1173\u20131179|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90482-9|issn=1090-2104|pmid=2}}</ref>\n\n[[Kinshasa]]-aligned forces included the Congolese national army under President [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila]] and later his son [[Joseph Kabila]], various anti foreigner [[Mai-Mai]] groups, and allied nations such as Zimbabwe, Angola, Chad, Sudan and Namibia. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>They control the west and south of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC). The main goal is the creation of a strong state in control of its territory and borders, and thus regaining control of the [[Natural resource|natural resources]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n[[Rwandan Patriotic Front]]-aligned forces included the national armies of the [[Tutsi]]-dominated governments of Rwanda and Burundi, the militia groups created by the ethnic Tutsi [[Banyamulenge]] residing in the DRC and the Banyamulenge-dominated [[Rally for Congolese Democracy]] (RCD) rebel forces based in Goma. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Tutsi-aligned forces inside the DRC are most active in North and South Kivu provinces, and have territory extending westward toward Kinshasa. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Goals include protecting the national security of Rwanda and Burundi, defending Tutsis in the DRC, checking the influence of Uganda and [[Mining industry of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|exploiting natural resources]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> \n\n[[Hutu]]-aligned forces included Rwandan Hutus responsible for the 1994 Rwandan Genocide, Burundian rebels seeking to overthrow their government, [[Congolese Hutu|Congolese Hutus]] and affiliated Mai-Mai militias. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bose|first=K. S.|last2=Sarma|first2=R. H.|date=1975-10-27|title=Delineation of the intimate details of the backbone conformation of pyridine nucleotide coenzymes in aqueous solution|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1173\u20131179|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90482-9|issn=1090-2104|pmid=2}}</ref>The major Hutu group currently is the [[Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda|Forces D\u00e9mocratiques de la Lib\u00e9ration du Rwanda]] (FDLR) operating in the Kivus. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Goals include expelling foreign Tutsi forces, ethnic cleansing of the Banyamulenge, overthrowing the governments of Rwanda and Burundi, and gaining control of resources.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Makar|first=A. B.|last2=McMartin|first2=K. E.|last3=Palese|first3=M.|last4=Tephly|first4=T. R.|date=1975-06|title=Formate assay in body fluids: application in methanol poisoning|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1|journal=Biochemical Medicine|volume=13|issue=2|pages=117\u2013126|doi=10.1016/0006-2944(75)90147-7|issn=0006-2944|pmid=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n[[Uganda]]-aligned forces included Uganda's national army and various Uganda-backed rebel groups, such as the [[Movement for the Liberation of the Congo|Movement for the Liberation of Congo]], in control of much of the northeast and central north of the DRC. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> Stated goals include protecting the borders of Uganda from invasion by [[DRC]]-based armed groups such as the [[Allied Democratic Forces]] and [[People's Redemption Army]], which may not exist, and destroying rebel bases in the DRC; Uganda had previously claimed that Joseph Kabila's government had failed to take action against these rebels. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The [[United Nations]] named Uganda as one country that illegally extracted natural resources from the DRC.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n== Kabila's march to Kinshasa ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=March 2011}}\nThe [[First Congo War]] began in 1996 as Rwanda grew increasingly concerned that members of [[Republican Rally for Democracy in Rwanda|Rassemblement D\u00e9mocratique pour le Rwanda]] militias, who were carrying out cross-border raids from [[Zaire]], were planning an invasion. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The new Tutsi-dominated government of Rwanda protested this violation of their [[territorial integrity]] and began to give arms to the ethnically Tutsi Banyamulenge of eastern Zaire. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bose|first=K. S.|last2=Sarma|first2=R. H.|date=1975-10-27|title=Delineation of the intimate details of the backbone conformation of pyridine nucleotide coenzymes in aqueous solution|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1173\u20131179|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90482-9|issn=1090-2104|pmid=2}}</ref> This intervention was vigorously denounced by the [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Mobutu government]] of Zaire, but he did not have any [[military capability]] to oppose, and little political capital to spend.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nWith active support from Rwanda, Uganda and Angola, Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila's rebel forces moved methodically down the Congo River, encountering only light resistance from Mobutu's crumbling regime based in Kinshasa. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> The bulk of Kabila's fighters were Tutsis and many were [[Veteran|veterans]] from conflicts in the [[African Great Lakes|Great Lakes region of Africa]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Kabila himself had credibility because he had been a longtime [[political opponent]] of Mobutu, and had been a follower of [[Patrice Lumumba]], the first Prime Minister of the independent Congo who was murdered and overthrown from power by a combination of internal and external forces, to be replaced by the then- Lieutenant General Mobutu in 1965. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bose|first=K. S.|last2=Sarma|first2=R. H.|date=1975-10-27|title=Delineation of the intimate details of the backbone conformation of pyridine nucleotide coenzymes in aqueous solution|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1173\u20131179|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90482-9|issn=1090-2104|pmid=2}}</ref>Kabila had declared himself a [[Marxism|Marxist]] and an admirer of [[Mao Zedong]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>He had been waging armed rebellion in eastern Zaire for nearly two decades, though, according to [[Che Guevara]]'s account of the early years of the conflict, he was an uncommitted and uninspirational leader. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bose|first=K. S.|last2=Sarma|first2=R. H.|date=1975-10-27|title=Delineation of the intimate details of the backbone conformation of pyridine nucleotide coenzymes in aqueous solution|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1173\u20131179|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90482-9|issn=1090-2104|pmid=2}}</ref>\n\nKabila's army began a slow movement westward in December 1996 near the end of the [[Great Lakes refugee crisis]], taking control of border towns and mines and solidifying control. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>There were reports of massacres and brutal repression by the rebel army. A [[United Nations Human Rights Council|UN human rights]] investigator published statements from witnesses claiming that Kabila's [[Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Congo|ADFLC]] engaged in massacres, and that as many as 60,000 civilians were killed by the advancing army (a claim strenuously denied by the ADFLC). <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>[[Roberto Garreton]] stated that his investigation in Goma turned up allegations of disappearances, torture and killings. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>He quoted [[Moise Nyarugabo]], an aide to Mobutu, as saying that killings and disappearances should be expected in wartime.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nKabila's forces launched an offensive in March 1997 and demanded the government surrender. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>On March 27 the rebels took [[Kasenga]]. The governments denied the rebel's success, starting a long pattern of false statements from the [[Defence minister|Defense Minister]] as to the progress and conduct of the war.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ardenne|first=M.|last2=Reitnauer|first2=P. G.|date=1975-09|title=[Demonstration of tumor inhibiting properties of a strongly immunostimulating low-molecular weight substance. Comparative studies with ifosfamide on the immuno-labile DS carcinosarcoma. Stimulation of the autoimmune activity for approx. 20 days by BA 1, a N-(2-cyanoethylene)-urea. Novel prophylactic possibilities]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1369\u20131379|issn=0004-4172|pmid=22}}</ref> [[Negotiation|Negotiations]] were proposed in late March and on April 2 a new Prime Minister was installed, [[\u00c9tienne Tshisekedi|Etienne Tshisekedi]], a long time rival of Mobutu. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Kabila, by this point in rough control of one quarter of the country, dismissed this as irrelevant, and warned Tshisekedi that he would have no part in a new government if he accepted the post.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the month of April the ADFLC made consistent progress down the river, and by May were on the outskirts of Kinshasa. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>On May 16, 1997 the multinational army headed by Kabila battled to secure [[Lubumbashi International Airport|Lubumbashi airport]] after [[Peace Talks (novel)|peace talks]] broke down and Mobutu fled the country. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>He died on September 7, 1997 in [[Morocco]]. After securing victory, Kabila controlled Kinshasa. He proclaimed himself President on the same day and immediately ordered a violent crackdown to restore order. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bose|first=K. S.|last2=Sarma|first2=R. H.|date=1975-10-27|title=Delineation of the intimate details of the backbone conformation of pyridine nucleotide coenzymes in aqueous solution|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1173\u20131179|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90482-9|issn=1090-2104|pmid=2}}</ref>He then began an attempt at reorganization of the nation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n== Unwelcomed \"support\" ==\n[[File:Second Congo War 2001 map en.png|thumb|Estimate of territory held by factions in 2001 to 2003.]]\n\nWhen Kabila gained control of the capital in May 1997, he faced substantial obstacles to governing the country that he renamed \"[[Democratic Republic of the Congo|the Democratic Republic of Congo]]\" (DRC). <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Beyond political jostling among various groups to gain power and an enormous [[external debt]], his foreign backers proved unwilling to leave when asked. The conspicuous Rwandan presence in the capital also rankled many Congolese, who were beginning to see Kabila as a pawn of foreign powers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nTensions reached new heights on 14 July 1998, when Kabila dismissed his Rwandan chief of staff, [[James Kabarebe]], and replaced him with a native Congolese, [[Celestin Kifwa]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Apparently Kabila felt that he had solidified his Congolese political base enough to put some distance between himself and the nations who had put him into power. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Although the move chilled what was already a troubled relationship with Rwanda, he softened the blow by making Kabarebe the military advisor to his successor.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nTwo weeks later Kabila abandoned such [[Diplomatics|diplomatic]] steps.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> He thanked Rwanda for their help, and ordered all Rwandan and Ugandan military forces to leave the country. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Isaac|first=O.|last2=Thiemer|first2=K.|date=1975-09|title=[Biochemical studies on camomile components/III. In vitro studies about the antipeptic activity of (--)-alpha-bisabolol (author's transl)]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1352\u20131354|issn=0004-4172|pmid=21}}</ref>Within 24 hours Rwandan military advisors living in Kinshasa were unceremoniously flown out. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The people most alarmed by this order were the Banyamulenge of eastern Congo. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Their tensions with neighboring ethnic groups had been a contributing factor in the genesis of the [[First Congo War]] and they were also utilized by Rwanda to affect events across the border in the DRC. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The Banyamulenge would again prove to be the spark of another conflagration.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n== 1998\u20131999 ==\nThe initial rebel offensive threatened the Kabila government in a matter of weeks. The government was only saved through the rapid intervention of a number of other African states. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ardenne|first=M.|last2=Reitnauer|first2=P. G.|date=1975-09|title=[Demonstration of tumor inhibiting properties of a strongly immunostimulating low-molecular weight substance. Comparative studies with ifosfamide on the immuno-labile DS carcinosarcoma. Stimulation of the autoimmune activity for approx. 20 days by BA 1, a N-(2-cyanoethylene)-urea. Novel prophylactic possibilities]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1369\u20131379|issn=0004-4172|pmid=22}}</ref>For a time it looked as if, as the rebel forces were forced back, an escalation in the conflict to a conventional war between multiple national armies loomed. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Such an outcome was avoided as battle lines stabilized in 1999. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>After that, the conflict was fought for much of the time by irregular [[Proxy war|proxy forces]] with little change in the territories held by the various parties.\n\nOn 2 August 1998 the [[Banyamulenge]] in the town of Goma erupted into mutiny. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Rwanda offered immediate assistance to the Banyamulenge and early in August a well-armed rebel group, the [[Rally for Congolese Democracy]] (RCD), composed primarily of Banyamulenge and backed by Rwanda and Uganda had emerged. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>This group quickly came to dominate the resource-rich eastern provinces and based its operations in the city of Goma. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The RCD quickly took control of the towns of [[Bukavu]] and [[Uvira]] in the [[Kivu|Kivus]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The [[Tutsi]]-led Rwandan government allied with Uganda, and Burundi also retaliated, occupying a portion of northeastern Congo. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Isaac|first=O.|last2=Thiemer|first2=K.|date=1975-09|title=[Biochemical studies on camomile components/III. In vitro studies about the antipeptic activity of (--)-alpha-bisabolol (author's transl)]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1352\u20131354|issn=0004-4172|pmid=21}}</ref>To help remove the occupying Rwandans, President Kabila enlisted the aid of the Hutu militants in eastern Congo and began to agitate public opinion against the Tutsis, resulting in several public lynchings in the streets of Kinshasa. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>On 12 August a loyalist army major broadcast a message urging resistance from a radio station in [[Bunia]] in eastern Congo: \"People must bring a machete, a spear, an arrow, a hoe, spades, rakes, nails, truncheons, electric irons, barbed wire, stones, and the like, in order, dear listeners, to kill the Rwandan Tutsis.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ardenne|first=M.|last2=Reitnauer|first2=P. G.|date=1975-09|title=[Demonstration of tumor inhibiting properties of a strongly immunostimulating low-molecular weight substance. Comparative studies with ifosfamide on the immuno-labile DS carcinosarcoma. Stimulation of the autoimmune activity for approx. 20 days by BA 1, a N-(2-cyanoethylene)-urea. Novel prophylactic possibilities]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1369\u20131379|issn=0004-4172|pmid=22}}</ref>\n\nThe Rwandan government also claimed a substantial part of eastern Congo as \"historically Rwandan\". <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Isaac|first=O.|last2=Thiemer|first2=K.|date=1975-09|title=[Biochemical studies on camomile components/III. In vitro studies about the antipeptic activity of (--)-alpha-bisabolol (author's transl)]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1352\u20131354|issn=0004-4172|pmid=21}}</ref>The Rwandans alleged that Kabila was organizing a genocide against their Tutsi brethren in the Kivu region. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The degree to which Rwandan intervention was motivated by a desire to protect the Banyamulenge, as opposed to using them as a smokescreen for its own regional aspirations, remains in question.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> In a bold move, RCD rebels hijacked a plane and flew it to the government base of [[Kitona]] on the Atlantic coast, where other mutinous government soldiers joined them. More towns in the east and around Kitona fell in rapid succession as the combined RCD, Rwandan, Burundian and Ugandan soldiers overwhelmed the government forces amid a flurry of ineffectual diplomatic efforts by various African nations. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ardenne|first=M.|last2=Reitnauer|first2=P. G.|date=1975-09|title=[Demonstration of tumor inhibiting properties of a strongly immunostimulating low-molecular weight substance. Comparative studies with ifosfamide on the immuno-labile DS carcinosarcoma. Stimulation of the autoimmune activity for approx. 20 days by BA 1, a N-(2-cyanoethylene)-urea. Novel prophylactic possibilities]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1369\u20131379|issn=0004-4172|pmid=22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>By 13 August, less than two weeks after the revolt began, the rebels held the Inga hydroelectric station that provided power to Kinshasa as well as the port of Matadi through which most of the Kinshasa's food passed. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ardenne|first=M.|last2=Reitnauer|first2=P. G.|date=1975-09|title=[Demonstration of tumor inhibiting properties of a strongly immunostimulating low-molecular weight substance. Comparative studies with ifosfamide on the immuno-labile DS carcinosarcoma. Stimulation of the autoimmune activity for approx. 20 days by BA 1, a N-(2-cyanoethylene)-urea. Novel prophylactic possibilities]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1369\u20131379|issn=0004-4172|pmid=22}}</ref>The diamond centre of Kisangani fell into rebel hands on 23 August and forces advancing from the east had begun to threaten Kinshasa by late August. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Uganda, while retaining joint support of the RCD with Rwanda, also created a rebel group that it supported exclusively, the [[Movement for the Liberation of the Congo|Movement for the Liberation of Congo]] (MLC).\n\nDespite the movement of the front lines, fighting continued throughout the country. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Even as rebel forces advanced on Kinshasa, government forces continued to battle for control of towns in the east of the country. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Isaac|first=O.|last2=Thiemer|first2=K.|date=1975-09|title=[Biochemical studies on camomile components/III. In vitro studies about the antipeptic activity of (--)-alpha-bisabolol (author's transl)]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1352\u20131354|issn=0004-4172|pmid=21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The Hutu militants with which Kabila was cooperating were also a significant force in the east. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Nevertheless, the fall of the capital and Kabila, who had spent the previous weeks desperately seeking support from various African nations and Cuba, seemed increasingly certain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nThe rebel offensive was abruptly reversed as Kabila's efforts at diplomacy bore fruit. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Congolese in the east and west showed a strong [[Nationalism|nationalistic]] sense and rejection of the second invasion of Rwandan and Ugandan forces in two years. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The first African countries to respond to Kabila's request for help were fellow members of the [[Southern African Development Community]] (SADC). <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>While officially the SADC members are bound to a [[Mutual Defense Treaty|mutual defense treaty]] in the case of outside aggression, many member nations took a neutral stance to the conflict.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ardenne|first=M.|last2=Reitnauer|first2=P. G.|date=1975-09|title=[Demonstration of tumor inhibiting properties of a strongly immunostimulating low-molecular weight substance. Comparative studies with ifosfamide on the immuno-labile DS carcinosarcoma. Stimulation of the autoimmune activity for approx. 20 days by BA 1, a N-(2-cyanoethylene)-urea. Novel prophylactic possibilities]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1369\u20131379|issn=0004-4172|pmid=22}}</ref> However, the governments of Namibia, Zimbabwe and Angola supported the Kabila government after a meeting in Harare, Zimbabwe on 19 August. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Several more nations joined the conflict for Kabila in the following weeks: Chad, Libya and Sudan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nA multi-sided war thus began. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>In September 1998, Zimbabwean forces flown into Kinshasa held off a rebel advance that reached the outskirts of the capital city while Angolan units attacked northward from its borders and eastward from the Angolan territory of Cabinda, against the besieging rebel forces. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>This [[intervention]] by various nations saved the Kabila government, and pushed the rebel front lines away from the capital. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>However, it was unable to defeat the rebel forces, and the advance threatened to escalate into direct conflict with the national armies of Uganda and Rwanda that formed part of the rebel movement.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> In November 1998 a new Ugandan-backed rebel group, the Movement for the Liberation of Congo was reported in the north of the country. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>On 6 November Rwandan President [[Paul Kagame]] admitted for the first time that Rwandan forces were assisting the RCD rebels for security reasons, apparently after a request by [[Nelson Mandela]] to advance [[Peace Talks (novel)|peace talks]]. On January 18, 1999 Rwanda, Uganda, Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe agreed on a ceasefire at a summit at Windhoek, Namibia but the RCD was not invited. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Fighting thus continued.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nOutside of Africa, most states remained neutral, but urged an end to the [[violence]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Non-African states were extremely reluctant to send troops to the region. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>A number of Western mining and diamond companies, most notably from the United States, Canada, Australia and Japan supported the Kabila government in exchange for business deals in both wars. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>These actions attracted substantial criticism from human rights groups.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n== Foreign supporters of the Congo government ==\n\n===== Zimbabwe =====\nThe Zimbabwean government sent troops to assist Kabila in 1998. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>President [[Robert Mugabe]], lured by Congo's rich natural resources and a desire to increase his own power and prestige in Africa, was the most ardent supporter of intervention on Kabila's behalf. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keighley|first=M. R.|last2=Asquith|first2=P.|last3=Edwards|first3=J. A.|last4=Alexander-Williams|first4=J.|date=1975-10|title=The importance of an innervated and intact antrum and pylorus in preventing postoperative duodenogastric reflux and gastritis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/123|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=62|issue=10|pages=845\u2013849|doi=10.1002/bjs.1800621024|issn=0007-1323|pmid=123}}</ref>Kabila and Mugabe had signed a US $200 million contract involving corporations owned by Mugabe and his family, and there were several reports in 1998 of numerous mining contracts being negotiated with companies under the control of the Mugabe family. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Mugabe resented being displaced by South African Nelson Mandela as the premier statesman of southern Africa.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Isaac|first=O.|last2=Thiemer|first2=K.|date=1975-09|title=[Biochemical studies on camomile components/III. In vitro studies about the antipeptic activity of (--)-alpha-bisabolol (author's transl)]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1352\u20131354|issn=0004-4172|pmid=21}}</ref> The war was a chance to confront another prominent African president, [[Yoweri Museveni]] of Uganda. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>As the head of the SADC's Organ on Politics, Defence and Security Mugabe believed he could reclaim his position as southern Africa's premiere statesmen by aiding Kabila. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Mugabe pitched the war as an effort to shore up a \"democratically elected government.\" <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Involvement in the war triggered a precipitous decline in Zimbabwe's economic performance and the value of the Zimbabwean dollar. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>In addition, it caused severe shortages of hard currency.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Angola ====\nThe Angolan government had fought against [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Mobutu S\u00e9s\u00e9 Seko]] in the [[First Congo War]] because of his support for rebel [[UNITA]] in the [[Angolan Civil War]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keighley|first=M. R.|last2=Asquith|first2=P.|last3=Edwards|first3=J. A.|last4=Alexander-Williams|first4=J.|date=1975-10|title=The importance of an innervated and intact antrum and pylorus in preventing postoperative duodenogastric reflux and gastritis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/123|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=62|issue=10|pages=845\u2013849|doi=10.1002/bjs.1800621024|issn=0007-1323|pmid=123}}</ref>The Angolan government wanted to eliminate UNITA operations in [[Southern Congolian forest-savanna mosaic|southern Congo]], which exchanged diamonds extracted from rebel-held Angola for foreign weapons.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> Angola had no confidence that a new president would be more effective than Kabila, and feared that continued fighting would lead to a power vacuum that could only help UNITA. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The intervention of the experienced Angolan forces was essential to decide the outcomes of both wars.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Namibia ====\nPresident Sam Nujoma had [[Interest (disambiguation)|interests]] in Congo similar to that of Mugabe, with several family members deeply involved in [[Congolese]] [[mining]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Namibia itself had few issues of national interest at stake in the war and the Namibian intervention was greeted with dismay and outrage by citizens and opposition politicians.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Chad ====\nKabila had originally discounted the possibility of support from [[African French|Francophone Africa]] but after a summit meeting in [[Libreville]], Gabon on 24 September, Chad agreed to send two thousand troops. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>France had encouraged Chad to join as a means of regaining influence in a region where the [[French language|French]] had retreated in disgrace after the 1994 Rwandan genocide.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Libya ====\nThe government of [[Muammar Gaddafi|Muammar al-Gaddafi]] provided the planes transporting the soldiers from Chad, which is surprising taking into consideration the uneasy relations between both countries. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Qaddafi may have seen a way to profit financially, but is also likely to have been strongly influenced by a desire to break out the international isolation imposed on Libya by the United States after the 1988 [[Pan Am Flight 103]] bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Sudan ====\nUnconfirmed reports in September indicated that [[Sudanese government]] forces were fighting rebels in [[Orientale Province|Orientale province]] close to the Sudanese and Ugandan borders. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>However, Sudan did not establish a significant military presence inside the DRC, though it continued to offer extensive [[support]] to three Ugandan rebel groups\u2014the [[Lord's Resistance Army]], the [[Uganda National Rescue Front II]] and the [[Allied Democratic Forces]]\u2014in retaliation for Ugandan support for the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n== 1999\u20132000 ==\nOn 5 April 1999 tensions within the RCD about the dominance of the Banyamulenge reached a peak when RCD leader [[Ernest Wamba dia Wamba]] moved his base from Goma to [[Uganda]]-controlled [[Kisangani]] to head a breakaway faction named [[Forces for Renewal]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>A further sign of a break occurred when Museveni of Uganda and Kabila signed a ceasefire accord on 18 April in Sirte, Libya following the mediation of Libyan President Muammar al-Gaddafi, and both the RCD and Rwanda refused to take part. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keighley|first=M. R.|last2=Asquith|first2=P.|last3=Edwards|first3=J. A.|last4=Alexander-Williams|first4=J.|date=1975-10|title=The importance of an innervated and intact antrum and pylorus in preventing postoperative duodenogastric reflux and gastritis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/123|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=62|issue=10|pages=845\u2013849|doi=10.1002/bjs.1800621024|issn=0007-1323|pmid=123}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keighley|first=M. R.|last2=Asquith|first2=P.|last3=Edwards|first3=J. A.|last4=Alexander-Williams|first4=J.|date=1975-10|title=The importance of an innervated and intact antrum and pylorus in preventing postoperative duodenogastric reflux and gastritis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/123|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=62|issue=10|pages=845\u2013849|doi=10.1002/bjs.1800621024|issn=0007-1323|pmid=123}}</ref>On 16 May, Wamba was ousted as head of the RCD in favour of a [[pro]]-Rwanda figure. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keighley|first=M. R.|last2=Asquith|first2=P.|last3=Edwards|first3=J. A.|last4=Alexander-Williams|first4=J.|date=1975-10|title=The importance of an innervated and intact antrum and pylorus in preventing postoperative duodenogastric reflux and gastritis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/123|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=62|issue=10|pages=845\u2013849|doi=10.1002/bjs.1800621024|issn=0007-1323|pmid=123}}</ref>Seven days later the various factions of the RCD clashed over control of Kisangani. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>On 8 June rebel factions met to try and create a common front against Kabila. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Despite these efforts, the creation by Uganda of the new province of Ituri sparked the ethnic clash of the [[Ituri conflict]], sometimes referred to as a \"war within a war\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, the diplomatic circumstances contributed to the first ceasefire of the war. In July 1999 the [[Lusaka Ceasefire Agreement]] was signed by the six warring countries (Democratic Republic of Congo, Angola, Namibia, Zimbabwe, Rwanda, and Uganda) and, on 1 August, the MLC. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The RCD refused to sign. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Under the agreement, forces from all sides, under a Joint Military Commission, would cooperate in tracking, disarming and documenting all armed groups in the Congo, especially those forces identified with the 1994 Rwandan Genocide. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Few provisions were made to actually disarm the militias.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United Nations Security Council]] deployed about 90 \u00a0[[liaison]] [[personnel]] in August 1999 to support the [[ceasefire]]. However, in the following months all sides accused the others of repeatedly breaking the cease-fire, and it became clear that small incidents could trigger attacks.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nThe tension between Uganda and Rwanda reached a breaking point in early August as units of the [[Uganda People's Defence Force|Uganda People\u2019s Defense Force]] and the [[Rwanda Defence Force|Rwandan Patriotic Army]] clashed in [[Kisangani]]. In November, government-controlled television in Kinshasa claimed that Kabila's army had been rebuilt and was now prepared to fulfill its \"mission to liberate\" the country.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> Rwandan forces launched a large offensive and approached Kinshasa before being repelled.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nBy February 24 2000, the UN authorized a force of 5,537 troops, the [[United Nations Organization Mission in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]] (known by the French acronym, MONUC), to monitor the cease-fire. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>However, fighting continued between rebels and government forces, and between Rwandan and Ugandan forces. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Numerous clashes and offensives occurred throughout the country, most notably heavy fighting between Uganda and Rwanda in Kisangani in May and June 2000. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>On 9 August 2000, a government offensive in [[Province of \u00c9quateur|Equateur Province]] was stopped along the [[Ubangi River|Ubangui River]] near [[Libenge]] by MLC forces.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> Despite the failure of military operations, diplomatic efforts made bilaterally or through the United Nations, [[African Union]] and [[Southern African Development Community]] failed to make any headway.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keighley|first=M. R.|last2=Asquith|first2=P.|last3=Edwards|first3=J. A.|last4=Alexander-Williams|first4=J.|date=1975-10|title=The importance of an innervated and intact antrum and pylorus in preventing postoperative duodenogastric reflux and gastritis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/123|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=62|issue=10|pages=845\u2013849|doi=10.1002/bjs.1800621024|issn=0007-1323|pmid=123}}</ref>\n\n== 2001 ==\nA bodyguard shot and wounded Laurent Kabila in an [[assassination]] attempt on 16 January 2001 in Zimbabwe. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Two days later Kabila died from his [[Injury|injuries]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>It is unknown who ordered the killing but most feel Kabila's allies were to blame as they were tired of his duplicity, in particular his failure to implement a detailed timetable for the introduction of a new [[democratic constitution]] leading to free and fair elections. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Angolan troops were highly visible at Kabila's funeral cortege in Kinshasa.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> By [[unanimous]] [[Voting|vote]] of the Congolese parliament, his son, Joseph Kabila, was sworn in as president to replace him. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>This was largely as a result of Robert Mugabe's backing and the fact that most parliamentarians had been [[HandPicked|handpicked]] by the elder Kabila. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>In February, the new president met Rwandan President Paul Kagame in the United States. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Rwanda, Uganda, and the rebels agreed to a UN pullout plan. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Uganda and Rwanda began pulling troops back from the front line.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n[[The Washington Post|The ''Washington Post'']] favorably contrasted Joseph Kabila\u2014Western educated and English-speaking\u2014with his father. Here was someone who made diplomats ''\"hope that things have changed\"'', whereas ''\"Laurent Kabila stood as the major impediment to a peaceful settlement of the war launched in August 1998 to unseat him.\"'' The Lusaka peace deal ''\"remained unfulfilled largely because he kept staging new offensives while blocking deployment of UN peacekeepers in government-held territory.\"'' An analyst from the London-based Economist Intelligence Unit is quoted saying ''\"The only obstruction had been Kabila because the [Lusaka] accord called for the government's democratic transition and that was a threat to his power.\"''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2001 a UN panel of experts investigated the illegal exploitation of diamonds, cobalt, coltan, gold and other lucrative resources in the Congo. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The report accused Rwanda, Uganda and Zimbabwe of systematically exploiting Congolese resources and recommended the Security Council impose sanctions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> Despite frequent accusations of misdeeds in the Congo, the Rwandan government continued to receive substantially more [[Aid|international aid]] than went to the vastly larger Congo. Rwandan President [[Paul Kagame]] was also still respected internationally for his leadership in ending the [[Rwandan genocide|Rwandan Genocide]] and for his efforts to rebuild and reuniting Rwanda.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n== 2002 ==\nA number of attempts to end the [[violence]] were made, but these were not successful. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>In 2002 Rwanda's situation began to worsen. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Many members of the RCD either gave up fighting or decided to join Kabila's government. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Moreover, the Banyamulenge, the backbone of Rwanda's militia forces, became increasingly tired of control from Kigali and the unending conflict. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>A number of them mutinied, leading to violent clashes between them and Rwandan forces. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>At the same time the western Congo was becoming increasingly [[secure]] under the younger [[Joseph Kabila|Kabila]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>International aid was resumed as inflation was brought under control.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ardenne|first=M.|last2=Reitnauer|first2=P. G.|date=1975-09|title=[Demonstration of tumor inhibiting properties of a strongly immunostimulating low-molecular weight substance. Comparative studies with ifosfamide on the immuno-labile DS carcinosarcoma. Stimulation of the autoimmune activity for approx. 20 days by BA 1, a N-(2-cyanoethylene)-urea. Novel prophylactic possibilities]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1369\u20131379|issn=0004-4172|pmid=22}}</ref>\n\n[[The Sun City Agreement]] was formalized on 19 April 2002. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ardenne|first=M.|last2=Reitnauer|first2=P. G.|date=1975-09|title=[Demonstration of tumor inhibiting properties of a strongly immunostimulating low-molecular weight substance. Comparative studies with ifosfamide on the immuno-labile DS carcinosarcoma. Stimulation of the autoimmune activity for approx. 20 days by BA 1, a N-(2-cyanoethylene)-urea. Novel prophylactic possibilities]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1369\u20131379|issn=0004-4172|pmid=22}}</ref>It was a framework for providing the Congo with a unified, multipartite government and [[Democratic election|democratic elections]]; however, [[Critic|critics]] noted that there were no [[Stipulation|stipulations]] regarding the [[unification]] of the army, which weakened the [[effectiveness]] of the [[agreement]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>There have been several reported breaches of the Sun City agreement, but it has seen a reduction in the fighting.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2002 Rwanda and the Democratic Republic of Congo signed a [[peace deal]] known as the [[Pretoria agreement|Pretoria Agreement]] after five days of talks in Pretoria, South Africa. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The talks centered on two issues.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>One was the withdrawal of the estimated 20,000 Rwandan soldiers in the Congo. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lefkowitz|first=R. J.|date=1975-09-15|title=Identification of adenylate cyclase-coupled beta-adrenergic receptors with radiolabeled beta-adrenergic antagonists|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1651\u20131658|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90001-5|issn=0006-2952|pmid=11}}</ref>The other was the rounding up of the ex-Rwandan soldiers and the dismantling of the Hutu militia known as [[Interahamwe]], which took part in Rwanda's 1994 genocide and continues to operate out of eastern Congo. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Rwanda had previously refused to [[Withdrawal|withdraw]] until the Hutu militias were dealt with.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nSigned on 6 September, the [[Luanda Agreement]] formalized peace between Congo and Uganda. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The treaty aimed to get Uganda to withdraw their troops from Bunia and to improve the relationship between the two countries, but implementation proved troublesome. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Eleven days later the first Rwandan soldiers were withdrawn from the eastern DRC.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> On 5 October Rwanda announced the completion of its withdrawal; MONUC confirmed the departure of over 20,000 Rwandan soldiers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October the [[United Nations|UN]] published its Expert Panel's Report of the pillage of natural resources by armed groups. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Isaac|first=O.|last2=Thiemer|first2=K.|date=1975-09|title=[Biochemical studies on camomile components/III. In vitro studies about the antipeptic activity of (--)-alpha-bisabolol (author's transl)]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21|journal=Arzneimittel-Forschung|volume=25|issue=9|pages=1352\u20131354|issn=0004-4172|pmid=21}}</ref>Both Rwanda and Uganda rejected accusations that senior political and military figures were involved in [[illicit]] [[trafficking]] of [[Plunderer|plundered]] [[Resource|resources]]. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Zimbabwe Defense Minister [[Sydney Sekeramayi]] says the Zimbabwean military withdrew from the DRC in October 2002, but in June 2006 reporters said a 50 man troop force had stayed in the DRC to protect Kabila.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 December 2002 the Congolese parties of the [[Inter Congolese Dialogue]], namely: the national government, the MLC, the RCD, the RCD-ML, the RCD-N, the domestic political opposition, representatives of civil society and the Mai Mai, signed the Global and All-Inclusive Agreement. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The Agreement described a plan for transitional governance that should have resulted in legislative and [[presidential election]] within two years of its signing and marked the formal end of the Second Congo War.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n== 2003 onwards: Transitional Government ==\nOn 18 July 2003, the [[Transitional government|Transitional Government]] came into being as specified in the [[Global]] and All-Inclusive Agreement out of the warring parties.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> The Agreement obliges the parties to carry out a plan to [[reunify]] the country, [[disarm]] and [[integrate]] the warring parties and hold elections.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> There have been numerous problems, resulting in continued instability in much of the country and a delay in the scheduled national elections from June 2005 to July 2006.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nThe main cause for the continued [[weakness]] of the Transitional Government is the refusal by the former warring parties to give up power to a centralized and neutral national administration. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Some belligerents maintained administrative and military command-and-control structures separate from that of the Transitional Government, but as the International Crisis Group has reported, these have gradually been reduced. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>A high level of official corruption siphoning money away from civil servants, soldiers and infrastructure projects causes further instability.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2006 the first elections were held in the DRC after the populace approved a new constitution. A second round was held on 30 October.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath and legacy==\n{{History of the DRC}}\n\n==== Areas of continuing conflict ====\nThe fragility of the state has allowed continued violence and [[human rights abuses]] in the east. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>There are three significant centers of [[conflict]]: North and South Kivu, where a weakened FDLR continues to threaten the Rwandan border and the Banyamulenge, and where Rwanda supports RCD-Goma rebels against Kinshasa; Ituri, where MONUC has proved unable to contain the numerous militia and groups driving the Ituri conflict; and northern Katanga, where Mai-Mai created by Laurent Kabila slipped out of the control of Kinshasa.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nThe [[ethnic violence]] between Hutu- and Tutsi-aligned forces has been a driving impetus for much of the conflict, with people on both sides fearing their annihilation as a race. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The Kinshasa- and Hutu-aligned forces enjoyed close relations as their interests in expelling the armies and proxy forces of Uganda and Rwanda dovetail. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>While the Uganda- and Rwanda-aligned forces worked closely together to gain territory at the expense of Kinshasa, competition over access to resources created a fissure in their relationship. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>There were reports that Uganda permitted Kinshasa to send arms to the Hutu FDLR via territory held by Uganda-backed rebels as Uganda, Kinshasa and the Hutus are all seeking, in varying degrees, to check the influence of Rwanda and its affiliates.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Rwanda's border security ====\nRwanda wants the DR Congo to stamp out the FDLR operating from its territory and has offered to send troops to help. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The Kinshasa government is [[Suspicion|suspicious]] of Kigali's influence over the region and its forces seem unable to deal with the FDLR. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Consequently Rwanda supports the continuing rebellion of General [[Laurent Nkunda]]. Final resolution will only happen when Rwanda feels its border is no longer threatened by Hutu rebels, and can stop supporting Nkunda: the two issues go hand in hand.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Militias ====\nThe Congo War has largely been one without large battles or clearly defined front lines. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>While significant numbers of trained soldiers from national armies have been involved, the rulers of those nations have been extremely loath to risk their forces in open combat. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The equipment and training of the national armies represents a major investment for the poor states of the region and losses would be difficult to replace. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The vast area of Congo dwarfs the armed groups, so military units have been based around strategically important strongholds such as ports, airfields, mining centers and the few passable roads, rather than guarding strictly defined areas of control.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\nAs a result the war has largely been fought by loosely organized militia groups. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>These untrained and undisciplined forces have greatly contributed to the violence of the conflict by frequent looting, rape and ethnic cleansing. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>It has also made peace far harder to enforce as the militias continue operating despite cease-fires between their patrons. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>These uncontrolled militias and their government allies have killed many Congolese. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Many more have died from disease and starvation brought about by the chaos in the region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Refugees ====\nEffects within the DRC include the displacement of some 3.4 million people, as well as the impoverishment of hundreds of thousands.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref> The majority of the displaced are from the eastern section of the country. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Nearly 2 million others have been displaced in the neighboring countries of Burundi, Rwanda, Tanzania and Uganda.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Pygmies ====\nThe Pygmies are believed to be the original inhabitants of the vast equatorial forests of Central Africa. During the war, Pygmies were hunted down like game animals and eaten. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Both sides of the war regarded them as \"[[subhuman]]\" and some say their flesh can confer magical powers. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>In neighbouring North Kivu province there has been [[cannibalism]] by a group known as [[Les Effacers]] ([[The Erasers]]) who wanted to clear the land of people to open it up for mineral exploitation. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>[[UN Human Rights Comitee|UN human rights]] activists reported in 2003 that Rwandan and Congolese rebels had carried out acts of cannibalism. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Sinafasi Makelo, a representative of Mbuti pygmies, has asked the [[United Nations Security Council|UN Security Council]] to recognise cannibalism as a crime against humanity and an act of genocide. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>According to [[Minority Rights Group International]] there is mass evidence of mass killings, cannibalism and rape of Pygmies and have urged the International Criminal Court to investigate a campaign of extermination against pygmies. Although, they have been targeted by virtually all the armed groups, much of the violence against Pygmies is attributed to the rebel group, the Movement for the Liberation of Congo, which is part of the transitional government and still controls much of the north, and their allies.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Effects on wildlife ====\nThe devastating effects on the economy and social institutions have led to serious impacts on the [[wildlife]] of the region. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>In September 2005 a survey reported by the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] showed the population of hippopotamuses in [[Virunga National Park]]'s [[Lake Edward]] has plummeted to less than 900 individuals from an estimated 29,000 thirty years previously. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The decline is attributed to poaching for meat as well as the teeth, which are used to produce illegal ivory. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>Additionally, about half of the world's 700 wild mountain gorillas live in the same park.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==== Legal consequences ====\nOn 19 December 2005 the [[United Nations International Court of Justice]] ruled that the DRC's sovereignty had been violated by Uganda, and that Uganda had looted billions of dollars worth of resources. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>The DRC government has asked for $10 billion in compensation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=J. M.|date=1975-09-15|title=The effect of adrenaline and of alpha- and beta-adrenergic blocking agents on ATP concentration and on incorporation of 32Pi into ATP in rat fat cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12|journal=Biochemical Pharmacology|volume=24|issue=18|pages=1659\u20131662|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(75)90002-7|issn=0006-2952|pmid=12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dongo conflict]], 2009 conflict in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] \n* [[List of wars by death toll]]\n* ''[[Living in Emergency: Stories of Doctors Without Borders]]'' \u2013 documentary film about the work of [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]] in DR Congo\n* [[Child soldiers in the Democratic Republic of Congo]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Baregu, Mwesiga. \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20130606221524/http://archive.lib.msu.edu/DMC/African%20Journals/pdfs/political%20science/volume7n2/ajps007002003.pdf The Clones of 'Mr. Kurtz': Violence, War and Plunder in the DRC].\" () ''[[African Journal of Political Science]]''. [[African Association of Political Science]]. (2002), Vol 7 No. 2. p.&nbsp;11\u201338. {{not a typo|1027-0353}}.\n* Berkeley, Bill. (2001) ''The Graves Are Not Yet Full: Race, Tribe, and Power in the Heart of Africa''. Basic Books. {{ISBN|0-465-00642-6}}. A narrative approach illustrating how political figures manipulate large groups into violence. Not focused on the current Congo conflict, but useful in understanding \"ethnic conflict\" generally in Africa.\n* [[John Clark (specialist)|Clark, John F.]] (2002) ''The African Stakes in the Congo War''. New York: Palgrave Macmillan. {{ISBN|1-4039-6723-7}}. Uses a political science approach to understanding motivations and power struggles, but is not an account of specific incidents and individuals.\n* Edgerton, Robert G. (2002) ''The Troubled Heart of Africa: A History of the Congo''. St. Martin's Press. {{ISBN|0-312-30486-2}}. There is a modicum of information on the troubles since 1996 in the latter sections.\n* Gondola, Ch. Didier. (2002) ''The History of Congo'', Greenwood Press, {{ISBN|0-313-31696-1}}. Covers events up to January 2002.\n* Miller, Eric. ''The Inability of Peacekeeping to Address the Security Dilemma''. 2010. {{ISBN|978-3-8383-4027-2}} . Covers the First and Second Congo Wars and its continued aftermath.\n* [[Gerard Prunier]], ''From Genocide to Continental War: The \"Congolese\" Conflict and the Crisis of Contemporary Africa'', C. Hurst & Co, 2009, {{ISBN|978-1-85065-523-7}}. Covers both the First and Second Congo Wars.\n* Renton, David; Seddon, David; Zeilig, Leo (2007). ''The Congo: Plunder & Resistance''. New York: Zed Books. {{ISBN|978-1-84277-485-4}}.\n* Stearns, Jason (2011). ''Dancing in the Glory of Monsters: The Collapse of the Congo and the Great War of Africa.'' New York: PublicAffairs. {{ISBN|978-1-58648-929-8}}.\n* Turner, Thomas. (2007) ''The Congo Wars: Conflict, Myth, and Reality''. New York: Zed Books. {{ISBN|978-1-84277-689-6}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|African World War}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/3075537.stm BBC Q&A on DR Congo conflict] \u2013 [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/country_profiles/1072684.stm BBC: Updated timeline of Congo history, with emphasis on the war]\n* [http://www.db.idpproject.org/Sites/idpSurvey.nsf/wViewCountries/7A07D857FEE42238C125683400554B57 Global IDP Database: Overview of warring parties]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/war/congo.htm Globalsecurity.org site on Congo Civil War]\n\n{{Armed groups in the Congo wars}}\n{{DRC topics}}\n{{Post-Cold War African conflicts}}\n\n[[Category:Wars involving the states and peoples of Africa]]\n[[Category:Civil wars involving the states and peoples of Africa]]\n[[Category:Second Congo War| ]]\n[[Category:History of Angola]]\n[[Category:History of Burundi]]\n[[Category:History of Chad]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:History of Namibia]]\n[[Category:History of Rwanda]]\n[[Category:History of Uganda]]\n[[Category:History of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:History of Zambia]]\n[[Category:Natural resource conflicts]]\n[[Category:Ethnicity-based civil wars]]\n[[Category:Proxy wars]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|War in Africa 1998 to 2003}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date = February 2016}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|image=[[File:DRC Rwanda line.jpg|122px|border]][[File:Congolese soldier.jpg|100px|border]]<br>[[File:Gbadolite.jpg|224px|border]]\n|caption= Rape victims who have been successfully reintegrated into their communities assemble {{small|(upper left)}}<br>Congolese rebel soldiers in 2001 {{small|(upper right)}}<br>Congolese rebel soldiers in the northern town of [[Gbadolite]] in 2000 {{small|(lower)}}\n|partof=the [[Congo Civil War (disambiguation)|Congo conflicts]] and the aftermath of the [[Rwandan genocide]]\n|conflict=Second Congo War\n|date=2 August 1998 \u2013 18 July 2003<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=08|day1=02|year1=1998|month2=07|day2=18|year2=2003}})\n|result= Military stalemate\n* [[Sun City Agreement]]\n* Creation of a unified, multi-party government in Congo, with [[Joseph Kabila]] as president and [[Jean-Pierre Bemba]] as prime minister.\n* [[Pretoria Accord]]; Rwandan withdrawal from Congo in exchange for commitment towards the disarmament of Hutu militias.\n* The [[Transitional Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]] is established, deployment of [[MONUC]].\n* Continuation of the [[Ituri conflict]].\n* Start of the [[Kivu conflict]].\n|place=[[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n|combatant1='''Pro-government:'''<br />{{flag|Democratic Republic of the Congo|1997|size=22px}}<br />{{ANG}}<br />{{CHA}}<br />{{NAM}}<br />{{ZWE}}<br />'''Anti-Ugandan forces:'''<br />{{Flagicon image|Flag of Lord's Resistance Army.svg|size=23px}} [[Lord's Resistance Army|LRA]]<br />{{SUD}} <small>(Alleged)</small>\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of ADF.png|size=23px}} [[Allied Democratic Forces|ADF]]\n* [[Uganda National Rescue Front|UNRF II]]\n* [[Nationalist and Integrationist Front|FNI]]\n'''Anti-Rwandan militias:'''<br />{{flagicon image|Flagge FDLR.svg}} [[Democratic Forces for the Li