{"title_page": "North Korean won", "text_new": "{{about|the official currency of North Korea|the official currency of South Korea|South Korean won}}\n{{distinguish|text = the [[Korean won]], the official currency of the [[Korean Empire]]}}\n{{short description|Official currency of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea}}\n{{Infobox Currency\n| image_1 =\n| iso_code = KPW\n| iso_number = 408\n| iso_exponent = 2\n| using_countries = {{flagcountry|PRK}}\n| inflation_rate        = \n| inflation_source_date = \n| subunit_ratio_1 = 1/100\n| subunit_name_1 = chon (\uc804/\u9322)\n| symbol = [[Won sign|\u20a9]]\n| no_plural = \n| frequently_used_coins =\n| rarely_used_coins = 1, 5, 10, 50 chon, \n\u20a91<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ccdailynews.com/section/?knum=125530 |script-title=ko:\ubd81\ud55c\uc758 \uc0c8\ub85c \ubc1c\ud589\ub41c \ud654\ud3d0\ub4e4 |date=December 4, 2009|publisher=ccdailynews.com|language=Korean}}</ref>\n|frequently_used_banknotes = \u20a9100, \u20a9200, \u20a9500, \u20a91000, \u20a92000, \u20a95000<ref>[http://banknotenews.com/files/17faa856f3e2e824d407e61c9f9c03c0-898.php North Korea revalues and replaces currency]. BanknoteNews.com. December 4, 2009.</ref>\n| rarely_used_banknotes = \u20a95, \u20a910, \u20a950\n| issuing_authority = [[Central Bank of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| title   = Democratic People's Republic of Korea won\n| hangul  = \uc870\uc120\ubbfc\uc8fc\uc8fc\uc758\uc778\ubbfc\uacf5\ud654\uad6d \uc6d0\n| hanja   = \u671d\u9bae\u6c11\u4e3b\u4e3b\u7fa9\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u5713\n| rr      = Joseon minjujuui inmin gonghwaguk won\n| mr      = Chos\u014fn minjuju\u016di inmin konghwakuk w\u014fn\n| context = north\n| img     =\n| caption =\n| othername1     = Korean People's won\n| hangul1        = \uc870\uc120\uc778 \uc6d0\n| hanja1         =\n| rr1            = Joseon-in won\n| mr1            = Chos\u014fn-in w\u014fn\n| koreanipa1     =\n| context1       = north\n}}\n\nThe '''North Korean won''' ({{IPAc-en|w|\u028c|n}};<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/won|title=won|website=[[OxfordDictionaries.com]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|access-date=8 January 2017}}</ref> {{Korean|hangul=\uc6d0|context=north}}, {{IPA-ko|w\u028cn}}; [[currency symbol|symbol]]: '''\u20a9'''; [[ISO 4217|code]]: '''KPW''') or '''Democratic People's Republic of Korea won''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \uc870\uc120\ubbfc\uc8fc\uc8fc\uc758\uc778\ubbfc\uacf5\ud654\uad6d \uc6d0) is the official currency of [[North Korea]]. It is subdivided into 100 ''chon''. The won is issued by the [[Central Bank of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea]], based in the capital city, [[Pyongyang]].\n\n== Etymology ==\n{{Main|Etymology of the Korean currencies}}\n''Won''<!-- (pronounced like the past tense of the English verb ''(to) win'')--> is a [[cognate]] of the [[Chinese yuan]] and [[Japanese yen]]. All three names derive from the [[Hanja]] {{lang|ko|[[wikt:\u5713|\u5713]]}}(\uc6d0), which means \"round shape.\" The won is subdivided into 100 chon (\uc804; \u9322; [[McCune-Reischauer]]: ''ch\u014fn''; [[Revised Romanization of Korea|Revised Romanization]]: ''jeon'').\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|History of the Korean currencies}}\n\n{{For|the Korean won before the North\u2013South division|Korean won}}\nThe won became the currency of North Korea on December 6, 1947, replacing the [[Korean yen]] that was still in circulation.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cho|first=Lee-Jay|author2=Kim, Yoon Hyung |title=Economic systems in South and North Korea: the agenda for economic integration|publisher=Korea Development Institute|year=1995|page=161|isbn=978-89-8063-001-1}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean won are intended exclusively for North Korean citizens, and the Bank of Trade (\ubb34\uc5ed\uc740\ud589) issued a separate currency (or [[foreign exchange certificate]]s) for visitors, like many other [[socialist state]]s. However, North Korea made two varieties of foreign exchange certificates, one for visitors from \"socialist countries\" which were colored red and hence nicknamed \"red won\",<ref name=\"dailynk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=5081|title=The Color of North Korean Money|publisher=|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref> and the other for visitors from \"capitalist countries\" which were colored blue/green and hence known as \"blue won\".<ref name=\"dailynk\" /> FECs were used until 1999, then officially abolished in 2002, in favor of visitors paying directly with hard currencies.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Linzmayer | first1 = Owen | title = The Banknote Book | chapter = North Korea | publisher = www.BanknoteNews.com | year = 2012 | location = San Francisco, CA | url = http://www.banknotebook.com}}</ref> Since at least 2012 foreign visitors (and privileged locals) can buy goods priced in 'tied' won using a local debit card, which they have to credit with exchanging foreign currency (Euro, [[United States dollar]] or [[Renminbi]]/Yuan) at the official bank rate. One euro would provide a credit of 130 won. This card can be used for instance at the famous [[Pyongyang Department Store No. 1]] or at the different stores at the international hotels, where the goods are priced at the tied won rate. This tied won does not exist in the form of bank notes. In normal stores and markets goods are priced in what has been called the 'untied' won or free market rate and regular banknotes can be used here. At for instance the [[Tongil Market]] and the Kwangbok Department Store (a.k.a. the Chinese Market) there are semi-official exchange agents who will give in regular banknotes around 10,000 won for one euro (2012) to locals and foreign visitors alike, so almost 77 times as much as the tied rate. However, the prices in the normal shops outside the tied won and restricted state shops are also based on this untied won rate.<ref>Black Market cash: the real value of N. Korean won, NK News, September 1, 2014 http://www.nknews.org/2014/09/black-market-cash-the-real-value-of-n-korean-won/</ref>\n\n=== Dollar peg removed ===\nSince 2001, the [[Government of North Korea|North Korean government]] has abandoned the iconic rate of 2.16 won to the dollar (which is said to have been based upon [[Kim Jong-il]]'s [[Day of the Shining Star|birthday]], February 16)<ref>{{cite book|last=Hoare|first=James|author2=Pares, Susan |title=North Korea in the 21st century: an interpretive guide|publisher=Global Oriental|year=2005|page=145|isbn=978-1-901903-96-6}}</ref> and banks in the country now issue at rates closer to the black market rate. More recent official rates have shown the North Korean won ({{as of|2017|01|07|lc=yes}}) to be \u20a9129.559 to the [[US dollar]].<ref name=\"xe_USDKPW\">[http://www.xe.com/ucc/convert.cgi?Amount=1&From=USD&To=KPW&image.x=14&image.y=20&image=Submit USD to KPW exchange rate, XE.com]. Retrieved 2010-06-22.</ref> However, rampant inflation has been eroding the North Korean won value. A report by [[North Korean defectors|defectors from North Korea]] claimed that the black market rate was \u20a9570 to the [[Chinese yuan]] (or about \u20a94,000 per U.S. dollar) in June 2009.<ref>Yong, Lee Sang (June 24, 2009). [http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=5081 The Color of North Korean Money]. ''[[Daily NK]]''.</ref> As of December 6, 2018, xe.com, a website that publishes mid-market currency exchange rates, lists the exchange rate at \u20a9900.073 to US$1.00.\n\n=== 2009 revaluation ===\nThe won was [[revaluation|revalued]] in November 2009<ref>Ho, Jung Kwon (November 30, 2009). [http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01500&num=5719 North Korea Replaces Currency] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212094537/http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01500&num=5719 |date=2009-12-12 }}. ''[[Daily NK]]''.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/02/business/global/02korea.html?_r=2 Choe Sang-Hun (December 9, 2009) ''New York Times'' (Global Business), \"North Korea Revalues Its Currency\"]</ref> for the first time in 50 years.<ref>The Wall Street Journal, Wednesday December 2, 2009 [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125963843649570793 North Korea Reissues Won, a Blow to Unofficial Economy]</ref><ref>The Wall Street Journal, Thursday December 3, 2009 [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125975276400572645 North Korea Begins Won Swap, Curfew]</ref>  North Koreans were given seven days to exchange a maximum of \u20a9100,000 (worth approximately US$40 on the black market) in \u20a91,000 notes for \u20a910 notes, but after protests by some of the populace{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}, the limit was raised to \u20a9150,000 in cash and \u20a9300,000 in bank savings.<ref name=wp>Harden, Blaine (December 2, 2009). [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/12/01/AR2009120101841.html?hpid=moreheadlines 'North Korea revalues currency, destroying personal savings']. ''[[The Washington Post]]''.</ref> The official exchange rate at this time was around $740 but black market value of the \u20a9150,000 was estimated to be near $30.<ref>Haggard, Stephen and Marcus Noland (January, 2009). [http://www.piie.com/publications/pb/pb10-01.pdf].</ref>  The revaluation, seen as a move against private market activity, wiped out many North Koreans' savings.<ref name=wp /> ''[[The Times]]'' speculated that the move may have been an attempt by the North Korean government to control price inflation and destroy the fortunes of local black market money traders.<ref name=\"The Times\" />  The announcement was made to foreign embassies but not in [[Media of North Korea|North Korean state media]].<ref name=\"The Times\">Parry, Richard Lloyd (December 2, 2009). [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6940482.ece North Koreans in shock as cash is 'banned']. ''[[The Times]]''.</ref><ref>[http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=112692&sectionid=351020405 Currency reform sparks anger in North Korea]. [[Press TV]]. December 2, 2009.</ref> Information was later carried via a wire-based radio service only available within North Korea.<ref>Hyun, Kim (December 2, 2009). [http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2009/12/02/9/0401000000AEN20091202009300315F.HTML N. Korea's official media silent about currency reform]. [[Yonhap]].</ref>\n\nAs part of the process, the old notes ceased to be legal tender on November 30, 2009, with notes valued in the new won not being distributed until December 7, 2009.<ref name=\"The Times\" />  This meant that North Koreans would not be able to exchange any money for goods or services until that date and most shops, restaurants and transport services had been shut down for the week.<ref name=\"The Times\" />  The only services that remained open were those catering to the political elite and foreigners which continued to trade exclusively in foreign currency.<ref name=\"The Times\" />  The measure had led to concerns amongst North Korean officials that it would result in [[civil unrest]]. China's [[Xinhua]] news agency described North Korean citizens in a \"collective panic\";<ref>[http://joongangdaily.joins.com/article/view.asp?aid=2913430 North\u2019s currency action shocking to its citizens]. ''[[Joongang Daily]]''. December 3, 2009.</ref> army bases were put on standby and there were unconfirmed reports of public protests in the streets in a handful of North Korean cities and towns that forced authorities to slightly increase the amount of currency people would be allowed to exchange.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/north-koreans-dare-to-protest-as-devaluation-wipes-out-savings-1833156.html|title=North Koreans dares to protest as devaluation wipes out savings|last=McNeil|first=David|date=December 3, 2009|work=[[The Independent]] | location=London}}</ref> Piles of old bills were also set on fire in separate locations across the country, old paper notes were dumped in a stream (against laws of the desecration of images of Kim Il-sung) and two black market traders were shot dead in the streets of [[Pyongsong]] by local police, according to international reports.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB126029137357982133?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_world|title=North Koreans Protest Currency Issue |last=Ramstad|first=Evan|date=December 9, 2009|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/asia/korea/2009/12/05/235359/North-Koreans.htm|title=North Koreans burn bills over currency reform|date=December 5, 2009|newspaper=[[The China Post]]}}</ref> Authorities threatened \"merciless punishment\" for any person who violated the rules of the currency change.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia-pacific/2009/12/200912371139615612.html|title=N Korea cash switch 'sparks panic' |date=December 3, 2009|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\nPictures of the new notes were published on December 4, 2009, in the ''[[Choson Sinbo|Chosun Shinbo]]'', a North Korean newspaper based in Japan.<ref name=\"dnk412\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk03100&num=5743|title=New Denomination Images Unveiled|last=Kook|first=Park Sung|date=December 4, 2009|newspaper=[[Daily NK]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2009/1204/p06s07-woap.html|title=North Korea admits drastic currency reform, is silent on protests|last=Kirk|first=Donald|date=December 4, 2009|newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]}}</ref> The paper claimed that the measure would weaken the free market and strengthen the country's socialist system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gnnLBoO7-ClzCc0ntsjmEiwe8i9w|title=Currency change cripples N.Korea markets: report|last=AFP|date=December 9, 2009}}</ref> However, the won plummeted 96 percent against the [[United States dollar|U.S. dollar]] in the ensuing days after revaluation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601080&sid=aw8p.PYArpkM|title=North Korean Won Plunges 96% After Government Revaluation |last=Lim|first=Bomi|date=December 9, 2009|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]}}</ref>  Authorities eventually raised the limit to 500,000 won, Chosun said, and promised no probe into savings of up to one million won and unlimited withdrawals if savings of more than one million are properly explained.\n\nIn February 2010, some of the curbs on the free market were eased and a senior party official sacked after incidents of unrest.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article7013254.ece|title=Food shortages and violence mount in North Korea as Utopian dream fails|last=Parry|first=Richard Lloyd|date=February 4, 2010|newspaper=[[The Times]] | location=London}}</ref> [[Pak Nam-gi]], the director of the Planning and Finance Department of North Korea's ruling Workers' Party, was executed later in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601080&sid=amrsl_DDQ7.A|title=North Korea Executes Official for Currency Reform, Yonhap Says|publisher=Bloomberg|date=March 17, 2010}}</ref> North Korea denied any serious crisis relating to the revaluation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=99VlXc5fwxA |title= North Korea Says No Chaos After Currency Reform  |publisher=Associated Press| date=April 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Coins ==\n\n=== Second Won ===\nThe first North Korean coins for circulation were minted in 1959 in denominations of 1, 5, and 10 chon. These coins were often restruck with the original dates in later years; however, 1970 and 1974 dates also appear on the 1 and 5 chon. In 1978, 50 chon coins featuring the [[Chollima Statue]] and a rising sun were introduced into circulation during the 1979 currency reform to allow greater flexibility for vendors by eliminating the 50 chon banknote and large amounts of \"small change\" coinage carried. In 1987, 1 won coins featuring the [[Grand People's Study House]] were introduced, but did not fully replace the 1 won note which remained legal tender.\n\nWhen the historic 2.16 peg to the dollar was abandoned in 2001 to allow for greater [[convertibility]] the coins began to lose value. After 2003, these coins were rarely seen in circulation but were still redeemable. Later, a new set of coins was introduced in 2005 in denominations of 5, 10, 50, and 100 won. These coins were less impressive compared to the older series, being very plain and generic in design. All circulation coins of the Second Won were struck in aluminum.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+Circulated coins\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Value !!colspan=\"2\"| Technical parameters !!colspan=\"2\"| Description !!colspan=\"4\"| Date of minted year\n|-\n! Diameter !! Composition !! Obverse !! Reverse !! General issue<br />(no star) !! Socialist visitor<br />(1 star) !! Capitalist visitor<br />(2 stars) !! Year last<br />circulated\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 1 chon || 16&nbsp;mm ||rowspan=\"9\"| [[Aluminium]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=Colin R.|author2=Michael, Thomas |title=Standard Catalog of World Coins 1901\u20132000|publisher=Krause Publications|year=2007|page=1313|isbn=978-0-89689-500-3}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"| State title, [[Emblem of North Korea|Coat of arms]], year of minting ||rowspan=\"3\"| Value, (optionally, star(s))\n|| 1959, 1970 || 1959 || 1959 || ?\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 5 chon || 18&nbsp;mm\n| 1959, 1974 || 1974 || 1974 || ?\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 10 chon || 20&nbsp;mm\n|| 1959 || 1959 || 1959 || ?\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 50 chon || 25&nbsp;mm\n| Bank title, Coat of arms, value || [[Chollima Statue]], year of minting,<br />(optionally, star(s))\n| 1978 || 1978 || 1978 || ?\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a91 || 27&nbsp;mm\n|rowspan=\"5\"| Bank title, Coat of arms, value, year of minting || [[Grand People's Study House]] || 1987 || N/A || N/A || ?\n|-|{{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a95 || 21&nbsp;mm ||rowspan=\"4\"| Value || 2005 || N/A || N/A || 2009\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a910 || 23&nbsp;mm || 2005 || N/A || N/A || 2009\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a950 || 25&nbsp;mm || 2005 || N/A || N/A || 2009\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a9100 || 27&nbsp;mm || 2005 || N/A || N/A || 2009\n|-\n|colspan=\"9\"|{{Standard coin table notice}}\n|}\n\nFollowing other [[state capitalist]] economies like Cuba and China, North Korea developed a special system of marking coins for two groups of foreign visitors. Issued in 1983, these coins were part of the \"Pakkundon\" convertible series. Coins with no \"stars\" were for general circulation in North Korea, coins marked with one star were for \"socialist visitors\", and coins marked with two stars were designated for \"capitalist visitors\". A fourth set, intended for collectors rather than circulation, was struck with the word \"specimen\" or \"example\" in Korean characters in the areas where the stars would be. The specimen/example set is the least common of the four. Besides the general circulating coins, there is an abundance of different commemorative coins minted in the name of the DPRK. Most, if not all of them, are sold to foreign [[numismatist]]s. Some of these are official, state approved coins, others are not.\n\n=== Third Won ===\nCoins were issued in 10, 50 chon and 1 won denominations in 2002 and 1 and 5 chon denominations in 2008. All denominations are struck in aluminum. These coins feature the national coat of arms on the obverse and flowers, particularly the [[Kimjongilia]] and the [[Kimilsungia]], on the reverse of the 10 and 50 chon. A magnolia adorns the 1 won.<ref name=\"dnk412\" />\n\nInitially struck in 2002, the coins were intended for use shortly after the dollar peg was removed from the currency. The 50 chon and 1 won were smaller than the previous designs, while the new 10 chon was the same size as the old. Hyperinflation became a very sudden reality, however, and the new coins were never released as planned. In 2008, 1 and 5 chon coins were also struck when a plan for monetary revaluation began. The coins were finally released into circulation in December 2009 but due to the flawed nature of the revaluation these coins again carry very little value, with especially the 1 and 5 chon being virtually irrelevant.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+Circulated coins\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Value !!colspan=\"3\"| Technical parameters !!colspan=\"2\"| Description !!rowspan=\"2\"| Date of minted year\n|-\n! Diameter !! Mass !! Composition !! Obverse !! Reverse\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 1 chon || 18.0&nbsp;mm || 0.8&nbsp;g ||rowspan=\"5\"| [[Aluminium]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwantallcoins.com/PRK.HTM|title=COINS OF PRK NORTH KOREA|publisher=|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>  <!--Likely to be same as before: [[Aluminium]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=Colin R.|author2=Michael, Thomas |title=Standard Catalog of World Coins 1901\u20132000|publisher=Krause Publications|date=2007|page=1313|isbn=978-0-89689-500-3}}</ref> --> ||rowspan=\"5\"| Coat of arms, Value || Royal azalea, Year of minting || 2008\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 5 chon || 19.0&nbsp;mm || 0.9&nbsp;g\n|| Tree peony, Year of minting || 2008\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 10 chon|| 20.0&nbsp;mm || 1.0&nbsp;g\n|| Azalea, Year of minting || 2002\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 50 chon || 22.1&nbsp;mm || 1.55&nbsp;g\n|| Kimjongilia, Year of minting || 2002\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a91 || 24.1&nbsp;mm || 1.9&nbsp;g\n|| Kimilsungia, Year of minting || 2002\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|{{Standard coin table notice}}\n|}\n\n== Banknotes ==\n\nThe first banknotes of \"North Korea\" were issued in 1945 by the Russian backed provisional government above the [[38th parallel north|38th parallel]]. These were in denominations of 1, 5, 10, and 100 won. These were discontinued shortly after Soviet forces withdrew and recognized the newly independent state.\n\n=== First Won ===\nThis currency was issued in all banknote form, with the first banknotes of this issue in denominations of 15, 20, and 50 chon along with 1, 5, 10 and 100 won in 1947. The chon notes had stylized art designs while the won denominations were fairly uniform in design featuring a farmer and a worker standing together and holding the symbolic tools. This currency was later revalued in 1959 at a rate of one new won to 100 old won to fix the inflation that had occurred as a result of the Korean War.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nautilus.org/DPRKBriefingBook/economy/DPRKMonetaryHistory.html|title=DPRK Economy|last=Schuler|first=Kurt|year=2004|publisher=Tables of Modern Monetary Systems|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301194517/http://www.nautilus.org/DPRKBriefingBook/economy/DPRKMonetaryHistory.html|archivedate=2010-03-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Second Won ===\nIn 1959, the old won was replaced with the Second Won, with price and exchange rates fixed to the U.S. dollar. This banknote series was issued in denominations of 50 chon, and 1, 5, 10, 50, and 100 won. These notes were much larger than the previous issue and depicted images representing various industries in the North Korean economy.\n\nIn 1979, the currency was again reformed, and a new banknote series was issued in denominations of 1, 5, 10, 50, and 100 won. There is ongoing speculation as to why this move was made. All 1959 banknotes were removed from circulation. Circulating coins, however, were not affected by this change. The designs for this issue were much more symbolic and charismatic than previous ones, with Kim Il-sung featuring for the first time on the 100 won note.\n\nIn 1992, another redesign was carried out for banknotes, again in denominations of 1-, 5-, 10-, 50-, and 100-won. Older notes were once again withdrawn. These notes were smaller and crisper than the previous issue and depicted more modern themes. The 5 and 10 won banknotes were again issued in 1998, along with a 500 won banknote that same year but were stamped rather than engraved reflecting poorer production quality. In 2002, 1,000 and 5,000 won notes were introduced, followed by a 200 won note in 2005. The former two were identical in design to the 100 won though differing in colors and added security features, but the colored fields behind the text no longer extended all the way to the margins. In 2007, the 500 won had also been revised in this same manner along with being engraved for the first time to protect against counterfeiting. From 1998 onwards, all notes were dated using the [[North Korean calendar|Juche year]] (Juche year) along with the standard dating.\n\nIn 2005, the Central Bank of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea issued commemorative 200, 500, 1000 and 5000 won notes to celebrate the 60th anniversary of the foundation of North Korea. It consists of an overprint on its regular issue notes.\n\nIn 2007, a commemorative version of this banknote series was released, stamped \"Great Leader Comrade Kim Il Sung's 95th Birthday\" on all denominations.\n\nAs explained above, there are two varieties of foreign certificates. For the 1978 banknote series, foreign certificates, called \"Pakkundon\", meaning \"exchangeable money\" were implemented by an overstamp and serial number color. This was intended to protect the value of the national currency in North Korea's [[command economy]]. These were first released in 1983 in two forms, one for \"socialist visitors\" which had a red stamp, and one for \"capitalist visitors\" which had a green stamp. Another series was released in 1986 with either a blue or red [[Guilloch\u00e9]] style stamp. These were issued in all denominations, except for the \u20a9100 note, presumably because it was assumed by the government that foreign visitors to North Korea would not show proper respect for its depiction of Kim Il-sung. These notes were discontinued in 1988 and replaced with a new series of Pakkundon in all banknote form that was more distinguishable and unmistakable from generic circulation currency.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+Banknotes of the North Korean won (1978 issue)\n|-\n! Obverse !! Reverse !! Main color !! Value !! Obverse !! Reverse\n|-\n| [[File:1978-1won-1-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-1won-2-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| Olive-green\n| \u20a91\n| A student, woman and children\n| Male and female soldiers; Yang Helyong (scenes from the opera ''[[Sea of Blood]]'')\n|-\n| [[File:1978-5won-1-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-5won-2-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| Blue-gray\n| \u20a95\n| Worker with a cogwheel and holding a political book; peasant woman holding a sheaf of wheat; factories in the background\n| [[Mount Kumgang]]\n|-\n| [[File:1978-10won-1-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-10won-2-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| Brown\n| \u20a910\n| [[Chollima]]\n| [[Chollima Steel Complex]]\n|-\n| [[File:1978-50won-1-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-50won-2-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| Olive-green\n| \u20a950\n| Soldier; peasant woman; officials of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n| Lake\n|-\n| [[File:1978-100won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-100won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| Brown and lilac\n| \u20a9100\n| [[Kim Il-sung]]\n| [[Mangyongdae-guyok|Mangyongdae]] (the birthplace of Kim Il-sung)\n|-\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+Variation of the 1978 series\n|-\n! Overstamp !! Serial number color !! Target users{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n|-\n| None || 1 red, 1 black || General circulation\n|-\n| Green with Korean text || 2 black || Socialist visitors 1983\n|-\n| Red with Korean text || 2 red || Capitalist visitors 1983\n|-\n| Red [[guilloch\u00e9]] with numeral || 2 red || Capitalist visitors 1986\n|-\n| Blue guilloch\u00e9 with numeral || 2 black || Socialist visitors 1986\n|}\n\nIn 1988, the Bank of Trade (\ubb34\uc5ed\uc740\ud589) (as opposed to the Central Bank) issued two unique series of foreign certificates. They both included 1 chon, 5 chon, 10 chon, 50 chon, \u20a91, \u20a95, \u20a910, and \u20a950. The series for \"capitalist visitors\" was blue-green, while the series for \"socialist visitors\" was pink.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=Colin R.|author2=Shafer, Neil |title=Standard Catalog of World Paper Money, Modern Issues, Volume 3|publisher=Krause Publications|year=1999|page=424|isbn=978-0-87341-746-4}}</ref> The chon notes had a simple design of patterns and corresponding values, while the socialist won notes depict the [[International Friendship Exhibition]], and the capitalist won notes depict the [[Chollima Statue]].<ref name=bn>[http://www.bank-note.org/nk.html Bank notes of the modern world \u2013 North Korea]. bank-note.org.</ref>\n\n[[Banknote]]s in circulation for the second won, up to December 2009, were as follows:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+1992 series\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Obverse !!rowspan=\"2\"| Reverse !!rowspan=\"2\"| Value !!rowspan=\"2\"| Dimensions !!rowspan=\"2\"| Main Color !!colspan=\"3\"| Description !!rowspan=\"2\"| Date of issue\n|-\n! Obverse !! Reverse !! Watermark\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-1won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-1won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a91\n| 116 \u00d7 55&nbsp;mm\n| Green\n| Actress Hong Yong-hee in her film role as ''[[The Flower Girl]]''\n| [[Mount Kumgang]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[Chollima Statue]]\n| 1992\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:HD-north-korea-1998-5-won-obverse.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:HD-north-korea-1998-5-won-reverse.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95\n| 126 \u00d7 60&nbsp;mm\n| Blue\n| Students, [[Kim Il-sung University]], [[Mangyongdae Children's Palace|Mangyongdae School Children's Palace]]\n| [[Grand People's Study House]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1992 <br />1998\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-10won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-10won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a910\n| 136 \u00d7 65&nbsp;mm\n| Brown-orange\n| Factory worker, [[Chollima]] (1,000 ri horse)\n| Pi Do Island, Western sea barrage and locks at Taedong River(Taedong-gang)\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-50won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-50won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a950\n| 146 \u00d7 70&nbsp;mm\n| Orange\n| Young professionals, [[Juche Tower]]\n| [[Paektu Mountain|Mount Paektu]]\n| [[Juche Tower]]\n| 1992\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-100won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-100won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9100\n| 156 \u00d7 75&nbsp;mm\n| Red and brown\n| [[Kim Il-sung]]\n| The birthplace of [[Kim Il-sung]], [[Mangyongdae-guyok]]\n| [[Arch of Triumph (Pyongyang)|Arch of Triumph]]\n| 1992\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:2005-200won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:2005-200won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9200\n| 140 \u00d7 72&nbsp;mm\n| Blue and green\n| [[Magnolia|Mongnan]] (National Flower of North Korea)\n| Value\n| [[Chollima Statue]]\n| 2005\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1998-500won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1998-500won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9500\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 156 \u00d7 75&nbsp;mm\n| Dark green\n| [[Kumsusan Palace of the Sun|Kumsusan Memorial Palace]]\n| [[Chongryu Bridge]]<ref name=\"Encyber\">{{citation|url=http://banknote.ws/COLLECTION/countries/ASI/KON/KON0044.htm|title=BANK NOTE MUSEUM|accessdate=2013-06-17}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[Arch of Triumph (Pyongyang)|Arch of Triumph]]\n| 1998<br />2007\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:HD-north-korea-1000-won-2006-obverse.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:HD-north-korea-1000-won-2006-reverse.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a91000\n| Green-cyan\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Kim Il-sung]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| The birthplace of [[Kim Il-sung]], [[Mangyongdae-guyok]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2002 <br />2006\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:2002-5000won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:2002-5000won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95000\n|Violet\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Third won ===\nIn 2009, another currency reform was initiated to tackle hyperinflation and black market activities. Unlike previous reforms, the 2009 move sparked a nationwide panic when it was announced there would be a two-week waiting period between the withdrawal of the old currency and the introduction of the new currency, coupled with an exchange limit of only 500,000 old won for each person, effectively wiping out savings. The state eventually pulled back on most exchange limits; however, the revaluation proved to be a failure.\n\nLike the coins for this series, some of the denominations were initially printed in 2002 but were never released into circulation, pointing to a planned monetary revaluation much earlier than 2009 that was never carried out.\n\nThe current series of banknotes of the third won are issued in denominations of 5-, 10-, 50-, 100-, 200-, 500-, 1,000-, 2,000-, and 5,000-won. [[Kim Il-sung]] is depicted only on the obverse of the highest denomination, with the 100 won note featuring the [[Magnolia]] (National Flower) and other notes depicting North Koreans of different professions and various monuments in North Korea.<ref name=\"dnk412\" /> The exchange rate was 100 second won to 1 third won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/|title=Aktuelle Nachrichten online|first=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|last=GmbH|publisher=|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnlike all previous series, these notes were all uniform in dimensions rather than staggered in size from smallest to largest. There are rumors that the original designs for the 1,000 and 2,000 won notes depicted Kim Il-sung and had similar design features to the 5,000 won that were scrapped and destroyed due to counterfeiters or thieves breaking into a bank warehouse and stealing early notes or printing materials, resulting in a total redesign of the two denominations in question.\n\nIn 2012, another commemorative series of banknotes was released, this time in the 2002\u20132009 series but similarly stamped \"Great Leader Comrade Kim Il Sung's 100th Birthday.\" Once again this stamp appeared on all denominations.<ref>[http://banknotenews.com/files/20a77c7620cccd7435f61161b2077912-2930.php North Korea new 100th birthday commemorative notes confirmed] BanknoteNews.com. March 14, 2014. Retrieved on 2014-07-09.</ref><ref>[http://banknotenews.com/files/52afbbe9fd47f8c08bf32043a14e86ce-3478.php North Korea new 5,000-won commemorative notes confirmed] BanknoteNews.com. May 26, 2015. Retrieved on 2015-05-27.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, 1,000 and 2,000 won notes were released with an overprint referencing the 70th Anniversary of its independence.\n\nOn July 25, 2014, a new 5,000 won note dated 2013 was released into circulation. Instead of depicting the portrait of North Korea's founder Kim Il-sung, the note depicts an image of his birthplace in Mangyondae and on the back the [[International Friendship Exhibition]] in [[Myohyangsan]] that displays gifts he and his son Kim Jong-il received from foreign leaders.<ref>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2014/08/11/2014081100747.html N.Korea Drops Kim Il-sung from New Banknotes] The Chosun Ilbo (english.chosun.com). August 11, 2014. Retrieved on 2014-08-11.</ref><ref>[http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01500&num=12160 NK Caught Off Guard by Disappearance of Kim] DailyNK (www.dailynk.com). August 1, 2014. Retrieved on 2014-08-13.</ref><ref>[http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?num=12215&cataId=nk00300 Past as Prelude: Kim Il Sung Will Reappear] DailyNK (www.dailynk.com). August 15, 2014. Retrieved on 2014-08-16.</ref><ref>[http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01500&num=14611 Residents avoiding use of old 5000 KPW notes] DailyNK (www.dailynk.com). July 11, 2017. Retrieved on 2017-08-11.</ref> There has been ongoing speculation that this could indicate plans for higher denominations to be released later which would depict Kim Il-sung, Kim Jong-il, or possibly both. However the official reason behind the change was to combat counterfeiters.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+2009 series<ref name=\"dnk412\" />\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"| Image !!rowspan=\"2\"| Value !!rowspan=\"2\"| Dimensions !!rowspan=\"2\"| Main Color !!colspan=\"3\"| Description !!rowspan=\"2\"| Date on notes !! rowspan=\"2\"|Remark\n|-\n! Obverse !! Reverse !! Obverse !! Reverse !! Watermark\n|-\n| [[File:HD-north-korea-5-won-2002-front.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:HD-north-korea-5-won-2002-back.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95\n| rowspan=10|145 \u00d7 65&nbsp;mm\n| Navy blue\n| Party members\n| [[Hwanggang Dam|Hwanggang hydroelectric dam]] and power station\n| rowspan=9|Mongnan(Seibold\u2019s magnolia) flowers\n!rowspan=\"3\"| Juche 91 (2002)\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:HD-north-korea-2002-10-won-front.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:HD-north-korea-2002-10-won-back.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a910\n| Olive Green\n| [[Korean People's Army|Soldiers]] ([[Korean People's Army Air Force|Air Force]], [[Korean People's Navy|Navy]], [[Korean People's Army Ground Force|Army]])\n| Victory Monument of the \"Fatherland Liberation War\" ([[Korean War]])\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:50 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:Nkorea92-50b.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a950\n| Purple\n| Engineer, farmer and working intellectual\n| [[Monument to Party Founding|Monument]] to the Founding of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:Nkorea08-100a (1).jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:100 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9100\n| Green\n| [[Magnolia|Mongnan]] (National Flower of North Korea)\n!rowspan=\"3\"| Value\n!rowspan=\"6\"| Juche 97 (2008)\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:200 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:Nkorea08-200b.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9200\n| Burgundy\n| [[Chollima statue|Chollima]]\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:500 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:500 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420-\u0440.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9500\n| Grey\n| [[Arch of Triumph (Pyongyang)|Arch of Triumph]]\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:Nkorea08-1000a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:Nkorea08-1000b.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a91000\n| Red\n| Birthplace of [[Kim Jong-suk]] in [[Hoeryong]]\n| [[Samji lake]]\n| The obverse depicts [[Kim Jong-suk]]\u2019s birthplace\n|-\n| [[File:Nkorea08-2000a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:2000 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a92000\n| Blue\n| Log cabin on [[Paektu Mountain|Mount Paektu]], Jong-il Peak\n| [[Paektu Mountain|Mount Paektu]]\n| The obverse depicts [[Kim Jong-il]]\u2019s [[Kim Jong-il#Birth|alleged]]<ref name=\"kim jong-il bbc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1907197.stm|title= Profile: Kim Jong-il|date=2009-01-16|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2009-12-11}}</ref> birthplace\n|-\n| [[File:Nkorea08-5000a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:Nkorea08-5000b.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95000\n| Brown\n| [[Kim Il-sung]]\n| [[Mangyongdae]]\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:North korea dprk 5000 won 2013.00.00 b58a pnl 0031333 f.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:2013 - 5000won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95000\n| Brown and pink\n| Birthplace of Kim Il-sung in [[Mangyongdae]]\n| [[International Friendship Exhibition]] in [[Myohyangsan|Mt. Myohang]]\n| Mongnan (Seibold\u2019s magnolia) flowers\n| '''Juche 102 (2013)'''\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n|colspan=\"10\"|{{Standard banknote table notice}}\n|}\n{{Exchange Rate|KPW|\nnote=Rates obtained from these websites could be substantially different from black market rate}}\n\n== Other currency used ==\n\nThe BBC reported in 2009 that in some department stores in [[Pyongyang]], the North Korean won is not accepted; the stores only take [[Japanese yen]] and [[United States dollar|U.S. dollars]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/in_pictures/8256890.stm | work=BBC News | title=In pictures: Life in poverty-stricken North Korea | date=September 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, most stores in North Korea take [[United States dollar|U.S. dollar]]s, [[euro]]s and Chinese yuan/[[renminbi]]. Since more renminbi and U.S. dollars are brought into the country than euros, change from transactions is primarily returned in renminbi or U.S. dollars.<ref>[https://www.rfa.org/english/news/korea/us-dollars-become-currency-of-choice-among-well-heeled-north-koreans-02212018162155.html US Dollars Become Currency of Choice Among Well-Heeled North Koreans] [[Radio Free Asia]] (www.rfa.org). February 21, 2018. Retrieved on 2018-12-29.</ref>{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Economy of North Korea]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.bis-ans-ende-der-welt.net/Nordkorea-B-En.htm|title=The banknotes of North Korea|language=en,de|editor=Heiko Otto|accessdate=2017-08-19}}\n\n{{n-start|title=North Korean won}}\n{{n-before|currency=[[Korean yen]]|reason=[[Division of Korea]] and moving toward a full sovereign nation from Allied occupation}}\n{{n-currency|location=[[North Korea]]|start=18 April 1980|end=12 April 2009|note=1st Won: 1945 to 1959<br />2nd Won (equivalent to 100 1st Won): 1959 to 2009<br />3rd Won (equivalent to 100 2nd Won): 2009 onwards}}\n{{n-after}}\n{{n-end}}\n\n{{Historical currencies of Korea}}\n{{Currencies of Asia}}\n{{Portal bar|Asia|Money|North Korea|Numismatics}}\n\n[[Category:Currencies of North Korea]]\n[[Category:Currencies introduced in 1947]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the official currency of North Korea|the official currency of South Korea|South Korean won}}\n{{distinguish|text = the [[Korean won]], the official currency of the [[Korean Empire]]}}\n{{short description|Official currency of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea}}\n{{Infobox Currency\n| image_1 =\n| iso_code = KPW\n| iso_number = 408\n| iso_exponent = 2\n| using_countries = {{flagcountry|PRK}}\n| inflation_rate        = \n| inflation_source_date = \n| subunit_ratio_1 = 1/100\n| subunit_name_1 = chon (\uc804/\u9322)\n| symbol = [[Won sign|\u20a9]]\n| no_plural = \n| frequently_used_coins =\n| rarely_used_coins = 1, 5, 10, 50 chon, \n\u20a91<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ccdailynews.com/section/?knum=125530 |script-title=ko:\ubd81\ud55c\uc758 \uc0c8\ub85c \ubc1c\ud589\ub41c \ud654\ud3d0\ub4e4 |date=December 4, 2009|publisher=ccdailynews.com|language=Korean}}</ref>\n|frequently_used_banknotes = \u20a9100, \u20a9200, \u20a9500, \u20a91000, \u20a92000, \u20a95000<ref>[http://banknotenews.com/files/17faa856f3e2e824d407e61c9f9c03c0-898.php North Korea revalues and replaces currency]. BanknoteNews.com. December 4, 2009.</ref>\n| rarely_used_banknotes = \u20a95, \u20a910, \u20a950\n| issuing_authority = [[Central Bank of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| title   = Democratic People's Republic of Korea won\n| hangul  = \uc870\uc120\ubbfc\uc8fc\uc8fc\uc758\uc778\ubbfc\uacf5\ud654\uad6d \uc6d0\n| hanja   = \u671d\u9bae\u6c11\u4e3b\u4e3b\u7fa9\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u5713\n| rr      = Joseon minjujuui inmin gonghwaguk won\n| mr      = Chos\u014fn minjuju\u016di inmin konghwakuk w\u014fn\n| context = north\n| img     =\n| caption =\n| othername1     = Korean People's won\n| hangul1        = \uc870\uc120\uc778 \uc6d0\n| hanja1         =\n| rr1            = Joseon-in won\n| mr1            = Chos\u014fn-in w\u014fn\n| koreanipa1     =\n| context1       = north\n}}\n\nThe '''North Korean won''' ({{IPAc-en|w|\u028c|n}};<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/won|title=won|website=[[OxfordDictionaries.com]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|access-date=8 January 2017}}</ref> {{Korean|hangul=\uc6d0|context=north}}, {{IPA-ko|w\u028cn}}; [[currency symbol|symbol]]: '''\u20a9'''; [[ISO 4217|code]]: '''KPW''') is the official currency of [[North Korea]]. It is subdivided into 100 ''chon''. The won is issued by the [[Central Bank of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea]], based in the capital city, [[Pyongyang]].\n\n== Etymology ==\n{{Main|Etymology of the Korean currencies}}\n''Won''<!-- (pronounced like the past tense of the English verb ''(to) win'')--> is a [[cognate]] of the [[Chinese yuan]] and [[Japanese yen]]. All three names derive from the [[Hanja]] {{lang|ko|[[wikt:\u5713|\u5713]]}}(\uc6d0), which means \"round shape.\" The won is subdivided into 100 chon (\uc804; \u9322; [[McCune-Reischauer]]: ''ch\u014fn''; [[Revised Romanization of Korea|Revised Romanization]]: ''jeon'').\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|History of the Korean currencies}}\n\n{{For|the Korean won before the North\u2013South division|Korean won}}\nThe won became the currency of North Korea on December 6, 1947, replacing the [[Korean yen]] that was still in circulation.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cho|first=Lee-Jay|author2=Kim, Yoon Hyung |title=Economic systems in South and North Korea: the agenda for economic integration|publisher=Korea Development Institute|year=1995|page=161|isbn=978-89-8063-001-1}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean won are intended exclusively for North Korean citizens, and the Bank of Trade (\ubb34\uc5ed\uc740\ud589) issued a separate currency (or [[foreign exchange certificate]]s) for visitors, like many other [[socialist state]]s. However, North Korea made two varieties of foreign exchange certificates, one for visitors from \"socialist countries\" which were colored red and hence nicknamed \"red won\",<ref name=\"dailynk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=5081|title=The Color of North Korean Money|publisher=|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref> and the other for visitors from \"capitalist countries\" which were colored blue/green and hence known as \"blue won\".<ref name=\"dailynk\" /> FECs were used until 1999, then officially abolished in 2002, in favor of visitors paying directly with hard currencies.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Linzmayer | first1 = Owen | title = The Banknote Book | chapter = North Korea | publisher = www.BanknoteNews.com | year = 2012 | location = San Francisco, CA | url = http://www.banknotebook.com}}</ref> Since at least 2012 foreign visitors (and privileged locals) can buy goods priced in 'tied' won using a local debit card, which they have to credit with exchanging foreign currency (Euro, [[United States dollar]] or [[Renminbi]]/Yuan) at the official bank rate. One euro would provide a credit of 130 won. This card can be used for instance at the famous [[Pyongyang Department Store No. 1]] or at the different stores at the international hotels, where the goods are priced at the tied won rate. This tied won does not exist in the form of bank notes. In normal stores and markets goods are priced in what has been called the 'untied' won or free market rate and regular banknotes can be used here. At for instance the [[Tongil Market]] and the Kwangbok Department Store (a.k.a. the Chinese Market) there are semi-official exchange agents who will give in regular banknotes around 10,000 won for one euro (2012) to locals and foreign visitors alike, so almost 77 times as much as the tied rate. However, the prices in the normal shops outside the tied won and restricted state shops are also based on this untied won rate.<ref>Black Market cash: the real value of N. Korean won, NK News, September 1, 2014 http://www.nknews.org/2014/09/black-market-cash-the-real-value-of-n-korean-won/</ref>\n\n=== Dollar peg removed ===\nSince 2001, the [[Government of North Korea|North Korean government]] has abandoned the iconic rate of 2.16 won to the dollar (which is said to have been based upon [[Kim Jong-il]]'s [[Day of the Shining Star|birthday]], February 16)<ref>{{cite book|last=Hoare|first=James|author2=Pares, Susan |title=North Korea in the 21st century: an interpretive guide|publisher=Global Oriental|year=2005|page=145|isbn=978-1-901903-96-6}}</ref> and banks in the country now issue at rates closer to the black market rate. More recent official rates have shown the North Korean won ({{as of|2017|01|07|lc=yes}}) to be \u20a9129.559 to the [[US dollar]].<ref name=\"xe_USDKPW\">[http://www.xe.com/ucc/convert.cgi?Amount=1&From=USD&To=KPW&image.x=14&image.y=20&image=Submit USD to KPW exchange rate, XE.com]. Retrieved 2010-06-22.</ref> However, rampant inflation has been eroding the North Korean won value. A report by [[North Korean defectors|defectors from North Korea]] claimed that the black market rate was \u20a9570 to the [[Chinese yuan]] (or about \u20a94,000 per U.S. dollar) in June 2009.<ref>Yong, Lee Sang (June 24, 2009). [http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=5081 The Color of North Korean Money]. ''[[Daily NK]]''.</ref> As of December 6, 2018, xe.com, a website that publishes mid-market currency exchange rates, lists the exchange rate at \u20a9900.073 to US$1.00.\n\n=== 2009 revaluation ===\nThe won was [[revaluation|revalued]] in November 2009<ref>Ho, Jung Kwon (November 30, 2009). [http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01500&num=5719 North Korea Replaces Currency] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212094537/http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01500&num=5719 |date=2009-12-12 }}. ''[[Daily NK]]''.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/02/business/global/02korea.html?_r=2 Choe Sang-Hun (December 9, 2009) ''New York Times'' (Global Business), \"North Korea Revalues Its Currency\"]</ref> for the first time in 50 years.<ref>The Wall Street Journal, Wednesday December 2, 2009 [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125963843649570793 North Korea Reissues Won, a Blow to Unofficial Economy]</ref><ref>The Wall Street Journal, Thursday December 3, 2009 [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125975276400572645 North Korea Begins Won Swap, Curfew]</ref>  North Koreans were given seven days to exchange a maximum of \u20a9100,000 (worth approximately US$40 on the black market) in \u20a91,000 notes for \u20a910 notes, but after protests by some of the populace{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}, the limit was raised to \u20a9150,000 in cash and \u20a9300,000 in bank savings.<ref name=wp>Harden, Blaine (December 2, 2009). [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/12/01/AR2009120101841.html?hpid=moreheadlines 'North Korea revalues currency, destroying personal savings']. ''[[The Washington Post]]''.</ref> The official exchange rate at this time was around $740 but black market value of the \u20a9150,000 was estimated to be near $30.<ref>Haggard, Stephen and Marcus Noland (January, 2009). [http://www.piie.com/publications/pb/pb10-01.pdf].</ref>  The revaluation, seen as a move against private market activity, wiped out many North Koreans' savings.<ref name=wp /> ''[[The Times]]'' speculated that the move may have been an attempt by the North Korean government to control price inflation and destroy the fortunes of local black market money traders.<ref name=\"The Times\" />  The announcement was made to foreign embassies but not in [[Media of North Korea|North Korean state media]].<ref name=\"The Times\">Parry, Richard Lloyd (December 2, 2009). [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6940482.ece North Koreans in shock as cash is 'banned']. ''[[The Times]]''.</ref><ref>[http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=112692&sectionid=351020405 Currency reform sparks anger in North Korea]. [[Press TV]]. December 2, 2009.</ref> Information was later carried via a wire-based radio service only available within North Korea.<ref>Hyun, Kim (December 2, 2009). [http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2009/12/02/9/0401000000AEN20091202009300315F.HTML N. Korea's official media silent about currency reform]. [[Yonhap]].</ref>\n\nAs part of the process, the old notes ceased to be legal tender on November 30, 2009, with notes valued in the new won not being distributed until December 7, 2009.<ref name=\"The Times\" />  This meant that North Koreans would not be able to exchange any money for goods or services until that date and most shops, restaurants and transport services had been shut down for the week.<ref name=\"The Times\" />  The only services that remained open were those catering to the political elite and foreigners which continued to trade exclusively in foreign currency.<ref name=\"The Times\" />  The measure had led to concerns amongst North Korean officials that it would result in [[civil unrest]]. China's [[Xinhua]] news agency described North Korean citizens in a \"collective panic\";<ref>[http://joongangdaily.joins.com/article/view.asp?aid=2913430 North\u2019s currency action shocking to its citizens]. ''[[Joongang Daily]]''. December 3, 2009.</ref> army bases were put on standby and there were unconfirmed reports of public protests in the streets in a handful of North Korean cities and towns that forced authorities to slightly increase the amount of currency people would be allowed to exchange.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/north-koreans-dare-to-protest-as-devaluation-wipes-out-savings-1833156.html|title=North Koreans dares to protest as devaluation wipes out savings|last=McNeil|first=David|date=December 3, 2009|work=[[The Independent]] | location=London}}</ref> Piles of old bills were also set on fire in separate locations across the country, old paper notes were dumped in a stream (against laws of the desecration of images of Kim Il-sung) and two black market traders were shot dead in the streets of [[Pyongsong]] by local police, according to international reports.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB126029137357982133?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_world|title=North Koreans Protest Currency Issue |last=Ramstad|first=Evan|date=December 9, 2009|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/asia/korea/2009/12/05/235359/North-Koreans.htm|title=North Koreans burn bills over currency reform|date=December 5, 2009|newspaper=[[The China Post]]}}</ref> Authorities threatened \"merciless punishment\" for any person who violated the rules of the currency change.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia-pacific/2009/12/200912371139615612.html|title=N Korea cash switch 'sparks panic' |date=December 3, 2009|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\nPictures of the new notes were published on December 4, 2009, in the ''[[Choson Sinbo|Chosun Shinbo]]'', a North Korean newspaper based in Japan.<ref name=\"dnk412\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk03100&num=5743|title=New Denomination Images Unveiled|last=Kook|first=Park Sung|date=December 4, 2009|newspaper=[[Daily NK]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2009/1204/p06s07-woap.html|title=North Korea admits drastic currency reform, is silent on protests|last=Kirk|first=Donald|date=December 4, 2009|newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]}}</ref> The paper claimed that the measure would weaken the free market and strengthen the country's socialist system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gnnLBoO7-ClzCc0ntsjmEiwe8i9w|title=Currency change cripples N.Korea markets: report|last=AFP|date=December 9, 2009}}</ref> However, the won plummeted 96 percent against the [[United States dollar|U.S. dollar]] in the ensuing days after revaluation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601080&sid=aw8p.PYArpkM|title=North Korean Won Plunges 96% After Government Revaluation |last=Lim|first=Bomi|date=December 9, 2009|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]}}</ref>  Authorities eventually raised the limit to 500,000 won, Chosun said, and promised no probe into savings of up to one million won and unlimited withdrawals if savings of more than one million are properly explained.\n\nIn February 2010, some of the curbs on the free market were eased and a senior party official sacked after incidents of unrest.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article7013254.ece|title=Food shortages and violence mount in North Korea as Utopian dream fails|last=Parry|first=Richard Lloyd|date=February 4, 2010|newspaper=[[The Times]] | location=London}}</ref> [[Pak Nam-gi]], the director of the Planning and Finance Department of North Korea's ruling Workers' Party, was executed later in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601080&sid=amrsl_DDQ7.A|title=North Korea Executes Official for Currency Reform, Yonhap Says|publisher=Bloomberg|date=March 17, 2010}}</ref> North Korea denied any serious crisis relating to the revaluation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=99VlXc5fwxA |title= North Korea Says No Chaos After Currency Reform  |publisher=Associated Press| date=April 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Coins ==\n\n=== Second Won ===\nThe first North Korean coins for circulation were minted in 1959 in denominations of 1, 5, and 10 chon. These coins were often restruck with the original dates in later years; however, 1970 and 1974 dates also appear on the 1 and 5 chon. In 1978, 50 chon coins featuring the [[Chollima Statue]] and a rising sun were introduced into circulation during the 1979 currency reform to allow greater flexibility for vendors by eliminating the 50 chon banknote and large amounts of \"small change\" coinage carried. In 1987, 1 won coins featuring the [[Grand People's Study House]] were introduced, but did not fully replace the 1 won note which remained legal tender.\n\nWhen the historic 2.16 peg to the dollar was abandoned in 2001 to allow for greater [[convertibility]] the coins began to lose value. After 2003, these coins were rarely seen in circulation but were still redeemable. Later, a new set of coins was introduced in 2005 in denominations of 5, 10, 50, and 100 won. These coins were less impressive compared to the older series, being very plain and generic in design. All circulation coins of the Second Won were struck in aluminum.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+Circulated coins\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Value !!colspan=\"2\"| Technical parameters !!colspan=\"2\"| Description !!colspan=\"4\"| Date of minted year\n|-\n! Diameter !! Composition !! Obverse !! Reverse !! General issue<br />(no star) !! Socialist visitor<br />(1 star) !! Capitalist visitor<br />(2 stars) !! Year last<br />circulated\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 1 chon || 16&nbsp;mm ||rowspan=\"9\"| [[Aluminium]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=Colin R.|author2=Michael, Thomas |title=Standard Catalog of World Coins 1901\u20132000|publisher=Krause Publications|year=2007|page=1313|isbn=978-0-89689-500-3}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"| State title, [[Emblem of North Korea|Coat of arms]], year of minting ||rowspan=\"3\"| Value, (optionally, star(s))\n|| 1959, 1970 || 1959 || 1959 || ?\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 5 chon || 18&nbsp;mm\n| 1959, 1974 || 1974 || 1974 || ?\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 10 chon || 20&nbsp;mm\n|| 1959 || 1959 || 1959 || ?\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 50 chon || 25&nbsp;mm\n| Bank title, Coat of arms, value || [[Chollima Statue]], year of minting,<br />(optionally, star(s))\n| 1978 || 1978 || 1978 || ?\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a91 || 27&nbsp;mm\n|rowspan=\"5\"| Bank title, Coat of arms, value, year of minting || [[Grand People's Study House]] || 1987 || N/A || N/A || ?\n|-|{{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a95 || 21&nbsp;mm ||rowspan=\"4\"| Value || 2005 || N/A || N/A || 2009\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a910 || 23&nbsp;mm || 2005 || N/A || N/A || 2009\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a950 || 25&nbsp;mm || 2005 || N/A || N/A || 2009\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a9100 || 27&nbsp;mm || 2005 || N/A || N/A || 2009\n|-\n|colspan=\"9\"|{{Standard coin table notice}}\n|}\n\nFollowing other [[state capitalist]] economies like Cuba and China, North Korea developed a special system of marking coins for two groups of foreign visitors. Issued in 1983, these coins were part of the \"Pakkundon\" convertible series. Coins with no \"stars\" were for general circulation in North Korea, coins marked with one star were for \"socialist visitors\", and coins marked with two stars were designated for \"capitalist visitors\". A fourth set, intended for collectors rather than circulation, was struck with the word \"specimen\" or \"example\" in Korean characters in the areas where the stars would be. The specimen/example set is the least common of the four. Besides the general circulating coins, there is an abundance of different commemorative coins minted in the name of the DPRK. Most, if not all of them, are sold to foreign [[numismatist]]s. Some of these are official, state approved coins, others are not.\n\n=== Third Won ===\nCoins were issued in 10, 50 chon and 1 won denominations in 2002 and 1 and 5 chon denominations in 2008. All denominations are struck in aluminum. These coins feature the national coat of arms on the obverse and flowers, particularly the [[Kimjongilia]] and the [[Kimilsungia]], on the reverse of the 10 and 50 chon. A magnolia adorns the 1 won.<ref name=\"dnk412\" />\n\nInitially struck in 2002, the coins were intended for use shortly after the dollar peg was removed from the currency. The 50 chon and 1 won were smaller than the previous designs, while the new 10 chon was the same size as the old. Hyperinflation became a very sudden reality, however, and the new coins were never released as planned. In 2008, 1 and 5 chon coins were also struck when a plan for monetary revaluation began. The coins were finally released into circulation in December 2009 but due to the flawed nature of the revaluation these coins again carry very little value, with especially the 1 and 5 chon being virtually irrelevant.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+Circulated coins\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Value !!colspan=\"3\"| Technical parameters !!colspan=\"2\"| Description !!rowspan=\"2\"| Date of minted year\n|-\n! Diameter !! Mass !! Composition !! Obverse !! Reverse\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 1 chon || 18.0&nbsp;mm || 0.8&nbsp;g ||rowspan=\"5\"| [[Aluminium]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwantallcoins.com/PRK.HTM|title=COINS OF PRK NORTH KOREA|publisher=|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>  <!--Likely to be same as before: [[Aluminium]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=Colin R.|author2=Michael, Thomas |title=Standard Catalog of World Coins 1901\u20132000|publisher=Krause Publications|date=2007|page=1313|isbn=978-0-89689-500-3}}</ref> --> ||rowspan=\"5\"| Coat of arms, Value || Royal azalea, Year of minting || 2008\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 5 chon || 19.0&nbsp;mm || 0.9&nbsp;g\n|| Tree peony, Year of minting || 2008\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 10 chon|| 20.0&nbsp;mm || 1.0&nbsp;g\n|| Azalea, Year of minting || 2002\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| 50 chon || 22.1&nbsp;mm || 1.55&nbsp;g\n|| Kimjongilia, Year of minting || 2002\n|- {{Coin-silver-color}}\n| \u20a91 || 24.1&nbsp;mm || 1.9&nbsp;g\n|| Kimilsungia, Year of minting || 2002\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|{{Standard coin table notice}}\n|}\n\n== Banknotes ==\n\nThe first banknotes of \"North Korea\" were issued in 1945 by the Russian backed provisional government above the [[38th parallel north|38th parallel]]. These were in denominations of 1, 5, 10, and 100 won. These were discontinued shortly after Soviet forces withdrew and recognized the newly independent state.\n\n=== First Won ===\nThis currency was issued in all banknote form, with the first banknotes of this issue in denominations of 15, 20, and 50 chon along with 1, 5, 10 and 100 won in 1947. The chon notes had stylized art designs while the won denominations were fairly uniform in design featuring a farmer and a worker standing together and holding the symbolic tools. This currency was later revalued in 1959 at a rate of one new won to 100 old won to fix the inflation that had occurred as a result of the Korean War.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nautilus.org/DPRKBriefingBook/economy/DPRKMonetaryHistory.html|title=DPRK Economy|last=Schuler|first=Kurt|year=2004|publisher=Tables of Modern Monetary Systems|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301194517/http://www.nautilus.org/DPRKBriefingBook/economy/DPRKMonetaryHistory.html|archivedate=2010-03-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Second Won ===\nIn 1959, the old won was replaced with the Second Won, with price and exchange rates fixed to the U.S. dollar. This banknote series was issued in denominations of 50 chon, and 1, 5, 10, 50, and 100 won. These notes were much larger than the previous issue and depicted images representing various industries in the North Korean economy.\n\nIn 1979, the currency was again reformed, and a new banknote series was issued in denominations of 1, 5, 10, 50, and 100 won. There is ongoing speculation as to why this move was made. All 1959 banknotes were removed from circulation. Circulating coins, however, were not affected by this change. The designs for this issue were much more symbolic and charismatic than previous ones, with Kim Il-sung featuring for the first time on the 100 won note.\n\nIn 1992, another redesign was carried out for banknotes, again in denominations of 1-, 5-, 10-, 50-, and 100-won. Older notes were once again withdrawn. These notes were smaller and crisper than the previous issue and depicted more modern themes. The 5 and 10 won banknotes were again issued in 1998, along with a 500 won banknote that same year but were stamped rather than engraved reflecting poorer production quality. In 2002, 1,000 and 5,000 won notes were introduced, followed by a 200 won note in 2005. The former two were identical in design to the 100 won though differing in colors and added security features, but the colored fields behind the text no longer extended all the way to the margins. In 2007, the 500 won had also been revised in this same manner along with being engraved for the first time to protect against counterfeiting. From 1998 onwards, all notes were dated using the [[North Korean calendar|Juche year]] (Juche year) along with the standard dating.\n\nIn 2005, the Central Bank of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea issued commemorative 200, 500, 1000 and 5000 won notes to celebrate the 60th anniversary of the foundation of North Korea. It consists of an overprint on its regular issue notes.\n\nIn 2007, a commemorative version of this banknote series was released, stamped \"Great Leader Comrade Kim Il Sung's 95th Birthday\" on all denominations.\n\nAs explained above, there are two varieties of foreign certificates. For the 1978 banknote series, foreign certificates, called \"Pakkundon\", meaning \"exchangeable money\" were implemented by an overstamp and serial number color. This was intended to protect the value of the national currency in North Korea's [[command economy]]. These were first released in 1983 in two forms, one for \"socialist visitors\" which had a red stamp, and one for \"capitalist visitors\" which had a green stamp. Another series was released in 1986 with either a blue or red [[Guilloch\u00e9]] style stamp. These were issued in all denominations, except for the \u20a9100 note, presumably because it was assumed by the government that foreign visitors to North Korea would not show proper respect for its depiction of Kim Il-sung. These notes were discontinued in 1988 and replaced with a new series of Pakkundon in all banknote form that was more distinguishable and unmistakable from generic circulation currency.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+Banknotes of the North Korean won (1978 issue)\n|-\n! Obverse !! Reverse !! Main color !! Value !! Obverse !! Reverse\n|-\n| [[File:1978-1won-1-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-1won-2-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| Olive-green\n| \u20a91\n| A student, woman and children\n| Male and female soldiers; Yang Helyong (scenes from the opera ''[[Sea of Blood]]'')\n|-\n| [[File:1978-5won-1-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-5won-2-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| Blue-gray\n| \u20a95\n| Worker with a cogwheel and holding a political book; peasant woman holding a sheaf of wheat; factories in the background\n| [[Mount Kumgang]]\n|-\n| [[File:1978-10won-1-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-10won-2-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| Brown\n| \u20a910\n| [[Chollima]]\n| [[Chollima Steel Complex]]\n|-\n| [[File:1978-50won-1-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-50won-2-a.jpg|x50px]]\n| Olive-green\n| \u20a950\n| Soldier; peasant woman; officials of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n| Lake\n|-\n| [[File:1978-100won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:1978-100won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| Brown and lilac\n| \u20a9100\n| [[Kim Il-sung]]\n| [[Mangyongdae-guyok|Mangyongdae]] (the birthplace of Kim Il-sung)\n|-\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+Variation of the 1978 series\n|-\n! Overstamp !! Serial number color !! Target users{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n|-\n| None || 1 red, 1 black || General circulation\n|-\n| Green with Korean text || 2 black || Socialist visitors 1983\n|-\n| Red with Korean text || 2 red || Capitalist visitors 1983\n|-\n| Red [[guilloch\u00e9]] with numeral || 2 red || Capitalist visitors 1986\n|-\n| Blue guilloch\u00e9 with numeral || 2 black || Socialist visitors 1986\n|}\n\nIn 1988, the Bank of Trade (\ubb34\uc5ed\uc740\ud589) (as opposed to the Central Bank) issued two unique series of foreign certificates. They both included 1 chon, 5 chon, 10 chon, 50 chon, \u20a91, \u20a95, \u20a910, and \u20a950. The series for \"capitalist visitors\" was blue-green, while the series for \"socialist visitors\" was pink.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=Colin R.|author2=Shafer, Neil |title=Standard Catalog of World Paper Money, Modern Issues, Volume 3|publisher=Krause Publications|year=1999|page=424|isbn=978-0-87341-746-4}}</ref> The chon notes had a simple design of patterns and corresponding values, while the socialist won notes depict the [[International Friendship Exhibition]], and the capitalist won notes depict the [[Chollima Statue]].<ref name=bn>[http://www.bank-note.org/nk.html Bank notes of the modern world \u2013 North Korea]. bank-note.org.</ref>\n\n[[Banknote]]s in circulation for the second won, up to December 2009, were as follows:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+1992 series\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Obverse !!rowspan=\"2\"| Reverse !!rowspan=\"2\"| Value !!rowspan=\"2\"| Dimensions !!rowspan=\"2\"| Main Color !!colspan=\"3\"| Description !!rowspan=\"2\"| Date of issue\n|-\n! Obverse !! Reverse !! Watermark\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-1won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-1won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a91\n| 116 \u00d7 55&nbsp;mm\n| Green\n| Actress Hong Yong-hee in her film role as ''[[The Flower Girl]]''\n| [[Mount Kumgang]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[Chollima Statue]]\n| 1992\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:HD-north-korea-1998-5-won-obverse.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:HD-north-korea-1998-5-won-reverse.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95\n| 126 \u00d7 60&nbsp;mm\n| Blue\n| Students, [[Kim Il-sung University]], [[Mangyongdae Children's Palace|Mangyongdae School Children's Palace]]\n| [[Grand People's Study House]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1992 <br />1998\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-10won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-10won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a910\n| 136 \u00d7 65&nbsp;mm\n| Brown-orange\n| Factory worker, [[Chollima]] (1,000 ri horse)\n| Pi Do Island, Western sea barrage and locks at Taedong River(Taedong-gang)\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-50won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-50won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a950\n| 146 \u00d7 70&nbsp;mm\n| Orange\n| Young professionals, [[Juche Tower]]\n| [[Paektu Mountain|Mount Paektu]]\n| [[Juche Tower]]\n| 1992\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-100won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1992-100won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9100\n| 156 \u00d7 75&nbsp;mm\n| Red and brown\n| [[Kim Il-sung]]\n| The birthplace of [[Kim Il-sung]], [[Mangyongdae-guyok]]\n| [[Arch of Triumph (Pyongyang)|Arch of Triumph]]\n| 1992\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:2005-200won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:2005-200won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9200\n| 140 \u00d7 72&nbsp;mm\n| Blue and green\n| [[Magnolia|Mongnan]] (National Flower of North Korea)\n| Value\n| [[Chollima Statue]]\n| 2005\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1998-500won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:1998-500won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9500\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 156 \u00d7 75&nbsp;mm\n| Dark green\n| [[Kumsusan Palace of the Sun|Kumsusan Memorial Palace]]\n| [[Chongryu Bridge]]<ref name=\"Encyber\">{{citation|url=http://banknote.ws/COLLECTION/countries/ASI/KON/KON0044.htm|title=BANK NOTE MUSEUM|accessdate=2013-06-17}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[Arch of Triumph (Pyongyang)|Arch of Triumph]]\n| 1998<br />2007\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:HD-north-korea-1000-won-2006-obverse.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:HD-north-korea-1000-won-2006-reverse.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a91000\n| Green-cyan\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Kim Il-sung]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| The birthplace of [[Kim Il-sung]], [[Mangyongdae-guyok]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2002 <br />2006\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:2002-5000won-1.jpg|x50px]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#000000\"| [[File:2002-5000won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95000\n|Violet\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Third won ===\nIn 2009, another currency reform was initiated to tackle hyperinflation and black market activities. Unlike previous reforms, the 2009 move sparked a nationwide panic when it was announced there would be a two-week waiting period between the withdrawal of the old currency and the introduction of the new currency, coupled with an exchange limit of only 500,000 old won for each person, effectively wiping out savings. The state eventually pulled back on most exchange limits; however, the revaluation proved to be a failure.\n\nLike the coins for this series, some of the denominations were initially printed in 2002 but were never released into circulation, pointing to a planned monetary revaluation much earlier than 2009 that was never carried out.\n\nThe current series of banknotes of the third won are issued in denominations of 5-, 10-, 50-, 100-, 200-, 500-, 1,000-, 2,000-, and 5,000-won. [[Kim Il-sung]] is depicted only on the obverse of the highest denomination, with the 100 won note featuring the [[Magnolia]] (National Flower) and other notes depicting North Koreans of different professions and various monuments in North Korea.<ref name=\"dnk412\" /> The exchange rate was 100 second won to 1 third won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/|title=Aktuelle Nachrichten online|first=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|last=GmbH|publisher=|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnlike all previous series, these notes were all uniform in dimensions rather than staggered in size from smallest to largest. There are rumors that the original designs for the 1,000 and 2,000 won notes depicted Kim Il-sung and had similar design features to the 5,000 won that were scrapped and destroyed due to counterfeiters or thieves breaking into a bank warehouse and stealing early notes or printing materials, resulting in a total redesign of the two denominations in question.\n\nIn 2012, another commemorative series of banknotes was released, this time in the 2002\u20132009 series but similarly stamped \"Great Leader Comrade Kim Il Sung's 100th Birthday.\" Once again this stamp appeared on all denominations.<ref>[http://banknotenews.com/files/20a77c7620cccd7435f61161b2077912-2930.php North Korea new 100th birthday commemorative notes confirmed] BanknoteNews.com. March 14, 2014. Retrieved on 2014-07-09.</ref><ref>[http://banknotenews.com/files/52afbbe9fd47f8c08bf32043a14e86ce-3478.php North Korea new 5,000-won commemorative notes confirmed] BanknoteNews.com. May 26, 2015. Retrieved on 2015-05-27.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, 1,000 and 2,000 won notes were released with an overprint referencing the 70th Anniversary of its independence.\n\nOn July 25, 2014, a new 5,000 won note dated 2013 was released into circulation. Instead of depicting the portrait of North Korea's founder Kim Il-sung, the note depicts an image of his birthplace in Mangyondae and on the back the [[International Friendship Exhibition]] in [[Myohyangsan]] that displays gifts he and his son Kim Jong-il received from foreign leaders.<ref>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2014/08/11/2014081100747.html N.Korea Drops Kim Il-sung from New Banknotes] The Chosun Ilbo (english.chosun.com). August 11, 2014. Retrieved on 2014-08-11.</ref><ref>[http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01500&num=12160 NK Caught Off Guard by Disappearance of Kim] DailyNK (www.dailynk.com). August 1, 2014. Retrieved on 2014-08-13.</ref><ref>[http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?num=12215&cataId=nk00300 Past as Prelude: Kim Il Sung Will Reappear] DailyNK (www.dailynk.com). August 15, 2014. Retrieved on 2014-08-16.</ref><ref>[http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01500&num=14611 Residents avoiding use of old 5000 KPW notes] DailyNK (www.dailynk.com). July 11, 2017. Retrieved on 2017-08-11.</ref> There has been ongoing speculation that this could indicate plans for higher denominations to be released later which would depict Kim Il-sung, Kim Jong-il, or possibly both. However the official reason behind the change was to combat counterfeiters.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+2009 series<ref name=\"dnk412\" />\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"| Image !!rowspan=\"2\"| Value !!rowspan=\"2\"| Dimensions !!rowspan=\"2\"| Main Color !!colspan=\"3\"| Description !!rowspan=\"2\"| Date on notes !! rowspan=\"2\"|Remark\n|-\n! Obverse !! Reverse !! Obverse !! Reverse !! Watermark\n|-\n| [[File:HD-north-korea-5-won-2002-front.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:HD-north-korea-5-won-2002-back.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95\n| rowspan=10|145 \u00d7 65&nbsp;mm\n| Navy blue\n| Party members\n| [[Hwanggang Dam|Hwanggang hydroelectric dam]] and power station\n| rowspan=9|Mongnan(Seibold\u2019s magnolia) flowers\n!rowspan=\"3\"| Juche 91 (2002)\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:HD-north-korea-2002-10-won-front.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:HD-north-korea-2002-10-won-back.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a910\n| Olive Green\n| [[Korean People's Army|Soldiers]] ([[Korean People's Army Air Force|Air Force]], [[Korean People's Navy|Navy]], [[Korean People's Army Ground Force|Army]])\n| Victory Monument of the \"Fatherland Liberation War\" ([[Korean War]])\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:50 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:Nkorea92-50b.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a950\n| Purple\n| Engineer, farmer and working intellectual\n| [[Monument to Party Founding|Monument]] to the Founding of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:Nkorea08-100a (1).jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:100 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9100\n| Green\n| [[Magnolia|Mongnan]] (National Flower of North Korea)\n!rowspan=\"3\"| Value\n!rowspan=\"6\"| Juche 97 (2008)\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:200 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:Nkorea08-200b.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9200\n| Burgundy\n| [[Chollima statue|Chollima]]\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:500 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:500 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420-\u0440.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a9500\n| Grey\n| [[Arch of Triumph (Pyongyang)|Arch of Triumph]]\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:Nkorea08-1000a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:Nkorea08-1000b.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a91000\n| Red\n| Birthplace of [[Kim Jong-suk]] in [[Hoeryong]]\n| [[Samji lake]]\n| The obverse depicts [[Kim Jong-suk]]\u2019s birthplace\n|-\n| [[File:Nkorea08-2000a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:2000 \u0432\u043e\u043d \u041a\u041d\u0414\u0420.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a92000\n| Blue\n| Log cabin on [[Paektu Mountain|Mount Paektu]], Jong-il Peak\n| [[Paektu Mountain|Mount Paektu]]\n| The obverse depicts [[Kim Jong-il]]\u2019s [[Kim Jong-il#Birth|alleged]]<ref name=\"kim jong-il bbc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1907197.stm|title= Profile: Kim Jong-il|date=2009-01-16|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2009-12-11}}</ref> birthplace\n|-\n| [[File:Nkorea08-5000a.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:Nkorea08-5000b.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95000\n| Brown\n| [[Kim Il-sung]]\n| [[Mangyongdae]]\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n| [[File:North korea dprk 5000 won 2013.00.00 b58a pnl 0031333 f.jpg|x50px]]\n| [[File:2013 - 5000won-2.jpg|x50px]]\n| \u20a95000\n| Brown and pink\n| Birthplace of Kim Il-sung in [[Mangyongdae]]\n| [[International Friendship Exhibition]] in [[Myohyangsan|Mt. Myohang]]\n| Mongnan (Seibold\u2019s magnolia) flowers\n| '''Juche 102 (2013)'''\n| <!-- Trivia -->\n|-\n|colspan=\"10\"|{{Standard banknote table notice}}\n|}\n{{Exchange Rate|KPW|\nnote=Rates obtained from these websites could be substantially different from black market rate}}\n\n== Other currency used ==\n\nThe BBC reported in 2009 that in some department stores in [[Pyongyang]], the North Korean won is not accepted; the stores only take [[Japanese yen]] and [[United States dollar|U.S. dollars]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/in_pictures/8256890.stm | work=BBC News | title=In pictures: Life in poverty-stricken North Korea | date=September 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, most stores in North Korea take [[United States dollar|U.S. dollar]]s, [[euro]]s and Chinese yuan/[[renminbi]]. Since more renminbi and U.S. dollars are brought into the country than euros, change from transactions is primarily returned in renminbi or U.S. dollars.<ref>[https://www.rfa.org/english/news/korea/us-dollars-become-currency-of-choice-among-well-heeled-north-koreans-02212018162155.html US Dollars Become Currency of Choice Among Well-Heeled North Koreans] [[Radio Free Asia]] (www.rfa.org). February 21, 2018. Retrieved on 2018-12-29.</ref>{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Economy of North Korea]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.bis-ans-ende-der-welt.net/Nordkorea-B-En.htm|title=The banknotes of North Korea|language=en,de|editor=Heiko Otto|accessdate=2017-08-19}}\n\n{{n-start|title=North Korean won}}\n{{n-before|currency=[[Korean yen]]|reason=[[Division of Korea]] and moving toward a full sovereign nation from Allied occupation}}\n{{n-currency|location=[[North Korea]]|start=18 April 1980|end=12 April 2009|note=1st Won: 1945 to 1959<br />2nd Won (equivalent to 100 1st Won): 1959 to 2009<br />3rd Won (equivalent to 100 2nd Won): 2009 onwards}}\n{{n-after}}\n{{n-end}}\n\n{{Historical currencies of Korea}}\n{{Currencies of Asia}}\n{{Portal bar|Asia|Money|North Korea|Numismatics}}\n\n[[Category:Currencies of North Korea]]\n[[Category:Currencies introduced in 1947]]\n", "name_user": "Mechanical Keyboarder", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Korean_won"}
{"title_page": "Milo\u0161 Timotijevi\u0107", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image = Portrait_of_Milo\u0161_Timotijevi\u0107.jpg\n| caption = Photo taken by Neboj\u0161a Babi\u0107\n| name        = Milo\u0161 Timotijevi\u0107\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1975|3|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Belgrade]], [[Yugoslavia]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| othername   =\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years active = 1995-present\n}}\n'''Milo\u0161 Timotijevi\u0107''' (born 9 March 1975) is a Serbian actor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Uniforma napokon sija |url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/spektakl.147.html:372157-Milos-Timotijevic-Uniforma-napokon-sija |website=Novosti |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He has appeared in more than sixty films and TV series since 1995. \n\nMilo\u0161 is best known for his roles in [[In the Land of Blood and Honey]] and [[Humidity (film)|Humidity]], for which he won the ''Best Actor Award'' at [[Belgrade International Film Festival]] in 2016.<ref name=\"An\u0111elina\">{{cite web |title=Holivud je prazna kanta |url=https://www.story.rs/celebrity-news/vesti/holivud-je-prazna-kanta-komentar-srpskog-glumca-o-saradnji-sa-andelinom-dzoli-je-samar-otreznjena/ |website=Story |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Winner of 44th FEST |url=http://2016.fest.rs/News/3491/The-Diary-of-a-Teenage-Girl-winner-of-44th-FEST.shtml |website=2016. FEST |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref> His most notable television works are crime thrillers [[South Wind (TV series)|South Wind]] and [[Besa (TV series)|Besa]], as well as acclaimed Serbian mystery [[Black Sun (TV Series)|Black Sun]].\n\n==Early life==\nMilo\u0161 showed interest in acting in early age. During primary and high school, he was a member of the Drama Studio of [[Radio Television of Serbia|Radio Television of Belgrade]], led by [[Mika Aleksi\u0107]]. After graduating from the high school, he attended the [[Faculty of Dramatic Arts, University of Arts in Belgrade|Faculty of Dramatic Arts]] in [[Belgrade]], where he graduated in the class of professors [[Milenko Mari\u010di\u0107]] and [[Branislav Mi\u0107unovi\u0107]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=An\u0111elina mi je dva puta dopisivala ulogu |url=https://www.ekapija.com/people/1395021/milos-timotijevic-glumac-andzelina-dzoli-mi-je-dva-puta-dopisivala-ulogu |website=Ekapija |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> His professional career started early during the studies.\n\n==Acting career==\n===1994\u20142015: Beginning ===\nHis first appearance on big screen was in 1995, when he was 20, with an episodic role in the historical series [[The End of the Obrenovi\u0107 Dynasty]]. After that, numerous roles ensued in different genres in both domestic and foreign production. The career start for Milo\u0161 wasn't easy, as it took almost 20 years to leave the supporting roles behind. Yet he said he was determined to become a real professional.<ref name=\"TVPrva\">{{cite web |title=Dvadeset godina sam \u010dekao glavnu ulogu |url=https://www.prva.rs/amp/133490/milos-timotijevic-20-godina-sam-cekao-glavnu-ulogu |website=Prva |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref> Early in his career he got to be known as dedicated and disciplined actor.<ref name=\"Politika\">{{cite web |title=Glumac mora da radi na sebi |url=https://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/28337/\u0413\u043b\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0446-\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0430-\u0434\u0430-\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438-\u043d\u0430-\u0441\u0435\u0431\u0438 |website=Politika |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He trained hard for 27 days only to be able to play the role of a bodybuilder in [[Seven and a Half]].<ref name=\"Politika\">{{cite web |title=Glumac mora da radi na sebi |url=https://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/28337/\u0413\u043b\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0446-\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0430-\u0434\u0430-\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438-\u043d\u0430-\u0441\u0435\u0431\u0438 |website=Politika |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> For the role of Emin in [[The Hornet]] (1998) he took a course in [[Albanian language|Albanian]].<ref name=\"Albanski\">{{cite web |title=Srbin, a ve\u010diti Albanac |url=https://www.telegraf.rs/amp/jetset/vesti-jetset/3016979-srbin-a-veciti-albanac-evo-kako-milos-timotijevic-objasnjava-to-sto-ga-uvek-biraju-za-ulogu-opasnog-tipa |website=Telegraf |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the years to come he shifted his focus to international cinema.<ref name=\"An\u0111elina\">{{cite web |title=Holivud je prazna kanta |url=https://www.story.rs/celebrity-news/vesti/holivud-je-prazna-kanta-komentar-srpskog-glumca-o-saradnji-sa-andelinom-dzoli-je-samar-otreznjena/ |website=Story |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He took a part in many foreign projects:  [[The November Man]], [[Chernobyl Diaries]] and [[In the Land of Blood and Honey]] ([[USA]]), [[The Sky Above Us (film)|The Sky Above Us]] ([[The Netherlands]]\u2014Serbia), [[The Last Panthers]] and [[Despite the Falling Snow]] ([[United Kingdom]]), as well as in Indian, German, Italian cinema and television. Timotijevi\u0107 also played Varlek in American TV series [[The Outpost (TV series)|The Outpost]] in 2018.\n\n===2016\u2014now: Career peak===\nOnly in the period of 2016 his career has extremely started to go up. In the movie [[Humidity (film)|Humidity]] (org. ''Vla\u017enost'') (Serbian - Greek - Dutch productions, premiered at the [[66th Berlin International Film Festival]]), Milo\u0161 played the main role which brought him award for the best actor at the [[Belgrade International Film Festival]] - ''FEST''.<ref name=\"TVPrva\">{{cite web |title=Dvadeset godina sam \u010dekao glavnu ulogu |url=https://www.prva.rs/amp/133490/milos-timotijevic-20-godina-sam-cekao-glavnu-ulogu |website=Prva |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref> The Serbian Section of the [[International Federation of Film Critics]] ''(FIPRESCI)'' also awarded Milo\u0161 the ''Best Actor Award''. The film has been screened at festivals around the world: in [[Vilnius]], [[Uruguay]], [[Northern Macedonia]], the [[Sarajevo Film Festival]], the Berlin Film Festival, [[Amsterdam]] and the [[Cannes Film Festival]].\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1994\n|''[[Obrenovi\u0107 dynasty|Kraj dinastije Obrenovi\u0107]]'' (TV series)\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n|''Simpatija i antipatija'' (TV movie)\n|[[Mihailo Obrenovi\u0107]]\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n|''[[Sre\u0107ni ljudi]]'' (TV series)\n|Pablo\n|\n|-\n| 1996\u20141997\n|''[[Gore dole]]'' (TV series)\n|Dejan\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n|''Raste trava'' (TV series)\n| Student\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[The Hornet]]''\n|Emin\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''Kanal Mimo'' (TV series)\n|\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''Thief\u2032s Comeback''\n|\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''Dosije 128'' (TV movie)\n|\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''Pronalaza\u010di'' (TV movie)\n|Police Inspector\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n|''[[The Crusaders (2001 film)|The Crusaders]]'' (TV movie)\n|Johann\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n|''[[Labyrinth (2002 film)|Labyrinth]]''\n|Tamara\u2019s Friend\n|\n|-\n| 2001\u20142002\n|''[[Porodi\u010dno blago]]'' (TV series)\n| Inspector Lazarevi\u0107\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Lisice (TV Show)|Lisice]]'' (TV series)\n|Petar\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''Pri\u010de o velikim matemati\u010darima'' (TV series)\n|Neboj\u0161a\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Seven and a Half]]''\n|Tadija\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n|''[[The Fourth Man (2007 film)|The Fourth Man]]''\n| Bodyguard\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n|''[[Vrati\u0107e se rode]]'' (TV series)\n| Ker (Hound)\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n|''Po\u010detak leta'' (short)\n|Branko\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n|''[[Bela la\u0111a]]'' (TV series)\n|Alamunja\u2019s Friend\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n|''Ma\u0161a''\n| Saki\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Bitter Fruit (2008 TV series)|Bitter Fruit]]'' (TV series)\n|\u0160eki\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''Drvo, kamen, oblak'' (short)\n|\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Human Zoo (film)|Human Zoo]]''\n| Boris\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Greh njene majke]]'' (TV series)\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n|''[[Kuku, Vasa]]'' (TV series)\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n|''[[Sva ta ravnica]]'' (TV series)\n|Josip\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n|''[[Selo gori, a baba se \u010de\u0161lja]]'' (TV series)\n|Doctor Zvonko\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n|''October''\n| Milo\u0161\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''\u010cuvar'' (short)\n|Bata\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[\u017dene sa Dedinja]]'' (TV series)\n|Hranislav Bekvalac\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''Practical Guide to Belgrade with Singing and Crying''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n|''[[In the Land of Blood and Honey]]''\n|Durja\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n|''[[Igra istine]]'' (TV series)\n| Moron\n|\n|-\n|2011\u20142012\n|''[[Nepobedivo srce]]'' (TV series)\n| Lieutenant\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''Sergeant'' (short)\n|\n|\n|-\n|2012\u20142020\n|''[[Military Academy (TV series)|Military Academy]]'' (TV series)\n| Lieutenant Vasiljevi\u0107\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Chernobyl Diaries]]''\n|Russian Check Point Guard\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n|''[[My Beautiful Country]]''\n|Igor\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n|''Prostor izme\u0111u nas'' (short)\n| Ivan\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Military Academy 2]]''\n| Lieutenant Vasiljevi\u0107\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Ravna Gora]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}'' (TV series)\n| Corporal \u010cuturi\u0107\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''Gli anni spezzati'' (TV series)\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n|''Odeljenje'' (TV series)\n|Inspector Cvijanovi\u0107\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n|''[[The November Man]]''\n| Federov\u2019s Chief of Staff\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[No One's Child]]''\n| Ilke\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''The Sky Above Us''\n| Marko\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[For King and Homeland]]''\n| Corporal \u010cuturi\u0107\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[The Last Panthers]]'' (TV series)\n| Bodyguard\n|\n|-\n| 2015\u20142016\n|''[[\u010cizma\u0161i]]'' (TV series)\n|Lieutenant Zdrako Zec\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Despite the Falling Snow]]''\n| First Man\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Humidity (film)|Humidity]]''\n| Petar\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[ZG80]]''\n|Rile\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Military Academy 3]]''\n|Captain Vaske\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''\u017divot traje tri dana'' (short)\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[Vivegam]]''\n|Bad Guy 1\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[Istine i la\u017ei]]'' (TV series)\n| Tasa\n|\n|-\n|2016\u20142017\n|''[[Sumnjiva lica]]'' (TV series)\n| Lukovac\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Shadows over Balkan|Black Sun]]'' (TV series)\n|Vojin \u0110uki\u0107\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Comic Sans (film)|Comic Sans]]''\n|Lukas\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[South Wind (film)|South Wind]]''\n| Stupar\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Dogs Die Alone]]''\n|Branko\n|\n|-\n| 2019\u20142020\n|''[[Besa (TV series)|Besa]]'' (TV series)\n| Petrit Koci\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[The Outpost (TV series)|The Outpost]]'' (TV series)\n| Varlek\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[The Team (film)|The Team]]''\n|Deki BMW\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Military Academy 5]]''\n|Captain Vaske\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[South Wind (TV series)|South Wind]]'' (TV series)\n|Stupar\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Heavens Above (film)|Heavens Above]]''\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|0863794}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timotijevic, Milos}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Serbian male film actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Serbian male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Serbian male actors]]\n\n\n{{Serbia-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image = Portrait_of_Milo\u0161_Timotijevi\u0107.jpg\n| caption = Photo taken by Neboj\u0161a Babi\u0107\n| name        = Milo\u0161 Timotijevi\u0107\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1975|3|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Belgrade]], [[Yugoslavia]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| othername   =\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years active = 1995-present\n}}\n'''Milo\u0161 Timotijevi\u0107''' (born 9 March 1975) is a Serbian actor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Uniforma napokon sija |url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/spektakl.147.html:372157-Milos-Timotijevic-Uniforma-napokon-sija |website=Novosti |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He has appeared in more than sixty films and TV series since 1995. \n\nMilo\u0161 is best known for his roles in [[In the Land of Blood and Honey]] and [[Humidity (film)|Humidity]], for which he won the ''Best Actor Award'' at [[Belgrade International Film Festival]] in 2016.<ref name=\"An\u0111elina\">{{cite web |title=Holivud je prazna kanta |url=https://www.story.rs/celebrity-news/vesti/holivud-je-prazna-kanta-komentar-srpskog-glumca-o-saradnji-sa-andelinom-dzoli-je-samar-otreznjena/ |website=Story |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> His most notable television works are crime thrillers [[South Wind (TV series)|South Wind]] and [[Besa (TV series)|Besa]], as well as acclaimed Serbian mystery [[Black Sun (TV Series)|Black Sun]].\n\n==Early life==\nMilo\u0161 showed interest in acting in early age. During primary and high school, he was a member of the Drama Studio of [[Radio Television of Serbia|Radio Television of Belgrade]], led by [[Mika Aleksi\u0107]]. After graduating from the high school, he attended the [[Faculty of Dramatic Arts, University of Arts in Belgrade|Faculty of Dramatic Arts]] in [[Belgrade]], where he graduated in the class of professors [[Milenko Mari\u010di\u0107]] and [[Branislav Mi\u0107unovi\u0107]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=An\u0111elina mi je dva puta dopisivala ulogu |url=https://www.ekapija.com/people/1395021/milos-timotijevic-glumac-andzelina-dzoli-mi-je-dva-puta-dopisivala-ulogu |website=Ekapija |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> His professional career started early during the studies.\n\n==Acting career==\n===1994\u20142015: Beginning ===\nHis first appearance on big screen was in 1995, when he was 20, with an episodic role in the historical series [[The End of the Obrenovi\u0107 Dynasty]]. After that, numerous roles ensued in different genres in both domestic and foreign production. The career start for Milo\u0161 wasn't easy, as it took almost 20 years to leave the supporting roles behind. Yet he said he was determined to become a real professional.<ref name=\"TVPrva\">{{cite web |title=Dvadeset godina sam \u010dekao glavnu ulogu |url=https://www.prva.rs/amp/133490/milos-timotijevic-20-godina-sam-cekao-glavnu-ulogu |website=Prva |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref> Early in his career he got to be known as dedicated and disciplined actor.<ref name=\"Politika\">{{cite web |title=Glumac mora da radi na sebi |url=https://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/28337/\u0413\u043b\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0446-\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0430-\u0434\u0430-\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438-\u043d\u0430-\u0441\u0435\u0431\u0438 |website=Politika |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He trained hard for 27 days only to be able to play the role of a bodybuilder in [[Seven and a Half]].<ref name=\"Politika\">{{cite web |title=Glumac mora da radi na sebi |url=https://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/28337/\u0413\u043b\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0446-\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0430-\u0434\u0430-\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438-\u043d\u0430-\u0441\u0435\u0431\u0438 |website=Politika |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> For the role of Emin in [[The Hornet]] (1998) he took a course in [[Albanian language|Albanian]].<ref name=\"Albanski\">{{cite web |title=Srbin, a ve\u010diti Albanac |url=https://www.telegraf.rs/amp/jetset/vesti-jetset/3016979-srbin-a-veciti-albanac-evo-kako-milos-timotijevic-objasnjava-to-sto-ga-uvek-biraju-za-ulogu-opasnog-tipa |website=Telegraf |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the years to come he shifted his focus to international cinema.<ref name=\"An\u0111elina\">{{cite web |title=Holivud je prazna kanta |url=https://www.story.rs/celebrity-news/vesti/holivud-je-prazna-kanta-komentar-srpskog-glumca-o-saradnji-sa-andelinom-dzoli-je-samar-otreznjena/ |website=Story |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He took a part in many foreign projects:  [[The November Man]], [[Chernobyl Diaries]] and [[In the Land of Blood and Honey]] ([[USA]]), [[The Sky Above Us (film)|The Sky Above Us]] ([[The Netherlands]]\u2014Serbia), [[The Last Panthers]] and [[Despite the Falling Snow]] ([[United Kingdom]]), as well as in Indian, German, Italian cinema and television. Timotijevi\u0107 also played Varlek in American TV series [[The Outpost (TV series)|The Outpost]] in 2018.\n\n===2016\u2014now: Career peak===\nOnly in the period of 2016 his career has extremely started to go up. In the movie [[Humidity (film)|Humidity]] (org. ''Vla\u017enost'') (Serbian - Greek - Dutch productions, premiered at the [[66th Berlin International Film Festival]]), Milo\u0161 played the main role which brought him award for the best actor at the [[Belgrade International Film Festival]] - ''FEST''.<ref name=\"TVPrva\">{{cite web |title=Dvadeset godina sam \u010dekao glavnu ulogu |url=https://www.prva.rs/amp/133490/milos-timotijevic-20-godina-sam-cekao-glavnu-ulogu |website=Prva |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref> The Serbian Section of the [[International Federation of Film Critics]] ''(FIPRESCI)'' also awarded Milo\u0161 the ''Best Actor Award''. The film has been screened at festivals around the world: in [[Vilnius]], [[Uruguay]], [[Northern Macedonia]], the [[Sarajevo Film Festival]], the Berlin Film Festival, [[Amsterdam]] and the [[Cannes Film Festival]].\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1994\n|''[[Obrenovi\u0107 dynasty|Kraj dinastije Obrenovi\u0107]]'' (TV series)\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n|''Simpatija i antipatija'' (TV movie)\n|[[Mihailo Obrenovi\u0107]]\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n|''[[Sre\u0107ni ljudi]]'' (TV series)\n|Pablo\n|\n|-\n| 1996\u20141997\n|''[[Gore dole]]'' (TV series)\n|Dejan\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n|''Raste trava'' (TV series)\n| Student\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[The Hornet]]''\n|Emin\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''Kanal Mimo'' (TV series)\n|\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''Thief\u2032s Comeback''\n|\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''Dosije 128'' (TV movie)\n|\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''Pronalaza\u010di'' (TV movie)\n|Police Inspector\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n|''[[The Crusaders (2001 film)|The Crusaders]]'' (TV movie)\n|Johann\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n|''[[Labyrinth (2002 film)|Labyrinth]]''\n|Tamara\u2019s Friend\n|\n|-\n| 2001\u20142002\n|''[[Porodi\u010dno blago]]'' (TV series)\n| Inspector Lazarevi\u0107\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Lisice (TV Show)|Lisice]]'' (TV series)\n|Petar\n|\n|-\n|2003