{"title_page": "Verve Forecast Records", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name        = Verve Forecast\n| image       = Verveforecastlogo.png\n| parent      = [[Universal Music Group]]\n| founded     = {{start date|1967}}\n| founder     = Jerry Schoenbaum\n| distributor = [[Verve Records|Verve]]\n| genre       = Various\n| country     = United States\n| website     = {{URL|verveforecast.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Verve Forecast''' is a record label formed as a division of Verve in 1967 to concentrate on pop, rock, and folk music.\n\n==Founding==\nJerry Schoenbaum of Verve and  [[Moe Asch]] of [[Folkways Records|Folkways]] created Verve Folkways in 1964 to take advantage of the popularity of folk music.<ref>{{cite web |title=Verve/Folkways: Marriage of Folk and Pop |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JikEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA12 |website=Google Books |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=23 November 2018 |date=21 January 1967}}</ref><ref name=\"Sternfield\">{{cite web |last1=Sternfield |first1=Aaron |title=Verve-Folkways Broadening Its Vista; Enters Deal with MGM |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YCkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA3 |website=Google Books |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=23 November 2018 |date=21 August 1965}}</ref> To broaden the label's appeal, the named was changed from Verve Folkways to Verve Forecast in 1967.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Claude |title=Nasatir's Nutrition Drive Beats Disks Artists Natural Attrition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2ycEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4 |website=Google Books |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=23 November 2018 |date=10 June 1967}}</ref> Schoenbaum was president of the label.<ref name=\"Unterberger\">{{cite book|last=Unterberger|first=Richie |title=Eight Miles High: Folk-rock's Flight from Haight-Ashbury to Woodstock |url=https://archive.org/details/eightmileshighfo00sanf |url-access=registration|accessdate=22 November 2018|year=2003|publisher=Backbeat Books|isbn=978-0-87930-743-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/eightmileshighfo00sanf/page/100 100]\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSchoenbaum left in 1969, and Verve Forecast was closed by its parent company, [[MGM Records|MGM]], in 1970.<ref name=\"Unterberger\" /> After [[PolyGram]] bought MGM, the Verve Forecast catalog was incorporated into [[Polydor Records|Polydor]]. The label was revived in the 1990s for [[smooth jazz]] releases by [[Chris Botti]], [[Jeff Lorber]], and [[Will Downing]]. When PolyGram merged with [[Universal Music Group|Universal]], the imprint was deactivated and its roster was transferred to [[GRP Records|GRP]]. In 2004, Verve Forecast was revived again to replace [[Blue Thumb Records|Blue Thumb]] to handle acts outside of jazz.\n\n==Roster==\nVerve Forecast signed pop, rock, folk, and blues musicians such as [[The Blues Project]], [[Caravan (band)|Caravan]], [[James Cotton]], [[Friend & Lover]], [[Tim Hardin]], [[Richie Havens]], [[The Hombres]], [[John Lee Hooker]], [[Lightnin' Hopkins]], [[Janis Ian]], [[Jim and Jean]], [[Lead Belly]], [[Bob Lind]], [[The New Lost City Ramblers]], [[Laura Nyro]], [[Odetta]], [[Street (band)|Street]], and [[Dave Van Ronk]].\n\nAfter 2004, the label included [[Blues Traveler]], [[Jamie Cullum]], [[Dion DiMucci|Dion]], [[Jesse Harris]], [[Katharine McPhee]], [[Mandy Moore]], [[Susan Tedeschi]], [[Teddy Thompson]], and [[Lizz Wright]].<ref name=\"AM credits\">{{cite web |title=Verve Forecast {{!}} Credits {{!}} AllMusic |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/verve-forecast-mn0000262606 |website=AllMusic |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vervelabelgroup.com/ Official site]\n\n{{vivendi}}\n\n[[Category:1967 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American record labels]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:Folk record labels]]\n[[Category:Labels distributed by Universal Music Group]]\n[[Category:Re-established companies]]\n[[Category:Record labels based in California]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Verve Forecast Records albums| ]]\n[[Category:Verve Forecast Records artists| ]]\n[[Category:Verve Forecast Records| ]]\n[[Category:Verve Records labels]]\n[[Category:Vivendi subsidiaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name        = Verve Forecast Records\n| image       = Verveforecastlogo.png\n| parent      = [[Universal Music Group]]\n| founded     = {{start date|1967}}\n| founder     = Jerry Schoenbaum\n| distributor = [[Verve Records|Verve]]\n| genre       = Various\n| country     = United States\n| website     = {{URL|verveforecast.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Verve Forecast Records''' is a record label formed as a division of Verve in 1967 to concentrate on pop, rock, and folk music.\n\n==Founding==\nJerry Schoenbaum of Verve and  [[Moe Asch]] of [[Folkways Records|Folkways]] created Verve Folkways in 1964 to take advantage of the popularity of folk music.<ref>{{cite web |title=Verve/Folkways: Marriage of Folk and Pop |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JikEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA12 |website=Google Books |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=23 November 2018 |date=21 January 1967}}</ref><ref name=\"Sternfield\">{{cite web |last1=Sternfield |first1=Aaron |title=Verve-Folkways Broadening Its Vista; Enters Deal with MGM |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YCkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA3 |website=Google Books |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=23 November 2018 |date=21 August 1965}}</ref> To broaden the label's appeal, the named was changed from Verve Folkways to Verve Forecast in 1967.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Claude |title=Nasatir's Nutrition Drive Beats Disks Artists Natural Attrition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2ycEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4 |website=Google Books |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=23 November 2018 |date=10 June 1967}}</ref> Schoenbaum was president of the label.<ref name=\"Unterberger\">{{cite book|last=Unterberger|first=Richie |title=Eight Miles High: Folk-rock's Flight from Haight-Ashbury to Woodstock |url=https://archive.org/details/eightmileshighfo00sanf |url-access=registration|accessdate=22 November 2018|year=2003|publisher=Backbeat Books|isbn=978-0-87930-743-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/eightmileshighfo00sanf/page/100 100]\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSchoenbaum left in 1969, and Verve Forecast was closed by its parent company, [[MGM Records|MGM]], in 1970.<ref name=\"Unterberger\" /> After [[PolyGram]] bought MGM, the Verve Forecast catalog was incorporated into [[Polydor Records|Polydor]]. The label was revived in the 1990s for [[smooth jazz]] releases by [[Chris Botti]], [[Jeff Lorber]], and [[Will Downing]]. When PolyGram merged with [[Universal Music Group|Universal]], the imprint was deactivated and its roster was transferred to [[GRP Records|GRP]]. In 2004, Verve Forecast was revived again to replace [[Blue Thumb Records|Blue Thumb]] to handle acts outside of jazz.\n\n==Roster==\nVerve Forecast signed pop, rock, folk, and blues musicians such as [[The Blues Project]], [[Caravan (band)|Caravan]], [[James Cotton]], [[Friend & Lover]], [[Tim Hardin]], [[Richie Havens]], [[The Hombres]], [[John Lee Hooker]], [[Lightnin' Hopkins]], [[Janis Ian]], [[Jim and Jean]], [[Lead Belly]], [[Bob Lind]], [[The New Lost City Ramblers]], [[Laura Nyro]], [[Odetta]], [[Street (band)|Street]], and [[Dave Van Ronk]].\n\nAfter 2004, the label included [[Blues Traveler]], [[Jamie Cullum]], [[Dion DiMucci|Dion]], [[Jesse Harris]], [[Katharine McPhee]], [[Mandy Moore]], [[Susan Tedeschi]], [[Teddy Thompson]], and [[Lizz Wright]].<ref name=\"AM credits\">{{cite web |title=Verve Forecast {{!}} Credits {{!}} AllMusic |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/verve-forecast-mn0000262606 |website=AllMusic |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vervelabelgroup.com/ Official site]\n\n{{vivendi}}\n\n[[Category:1967 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American record labels]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:Folk record labels]]\n[[Category:Labels distributed by Universal Music Group]]\n[[Category:Re-established companies]]\n[[Category:Record labels based in California]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Verve Forecast Records albums| ]]\n[[Category:Verve Forecast Records artists| ]]\n[[Category:Verve Forecast Records| ]]\n[[Category:Verve Records labels]]\n[[Category:Vivendi subsidiaries]]\n", "name_user": "VLGEdit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verve_Forecast_Records"}
